{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1780926431351,"sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","part":{"id":"prt_ea77cc074001gvutObQpPguG7C","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"634b1b5fcaea757bb34acfdb0193dd5bdc98fa26","messageID":"msg_ea77ca512001nUL8mcSDQSzhwj","sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":44299,"input":581,"output":155,"reasoning":43,"cache":{"write":0,"read":43520}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780926433615,"sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","part":{"id":"prt_ea77cc94a001tzKHj6hg6bjohy","messageID":"msg_ea77cc18a001W0nhx4yXBV8BDy","sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","snapshot":"05befa738c891a3dcc720c95f5290b5d5420f706","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1780926450414,"sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","part":{"id":"prt_ea77cdb01001U7ijUC84hL228F","messageID":"msg_ea77cc18a001W0nhx4yXBV8BDy","sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","type":"text","text":"The files are under `.opencode/specs/...` rather than root `specs/...`; I found the requested 010 phase and am reading those ten files now.","time":{"start":1780926438145,"end":1780926450407},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_036408d1c76c14fc016a26c7e61f34819194e4ac0e87ba7253","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780926450553,"sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_bw4ROZz1gIc0OyTIeRcGoNmS","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-001.md","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-001.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 001 — Hybrid recall + blended scoring + explainability\n2: \n3: **Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.70 · **tokens:** 93394 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n4: \n5: ---\n6: \n7: ## Mechanism\n8: OpenLTM recall is lexical-candidate-first. `recall()` tokenizes the query, quotes every token, joins them with `OR`, then runs `memories_fts MATCH ? ORDER BY rank LIMIT 50` against FTS5; it records BM25-ish ranks as `Math.exp(rank)` because SQLite FTS5 rank is negative and closer to zero is better (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:425-442`). If the FTS candidate set is smaller than the requested `limit`, semantic fallback runs when `ltm.semanticFallback !== false`, calling `getSimilarMemories(query, limit * 2, 0.5)` and merging semantic ids/scores into the same id set (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:444-456`, `packages/openltm-core/src/config.ts:64-72`). Semantic search uses sqlite-vec KNN when available, otherwise brute-force cosine over stored embeddings, with a `similarity >= threshold` filter (`packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:261-301`).\n9: \n10: The merged set is filtered by tags, category, project scope, workspace, agent, and `status = 'active'` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:464-510`). The hot path excludes the embedding blob from result rows (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:521-533`). The actual query-result sorter does **not** sort by the explainer’s 40/35/15/10 blended score; it sorts by materialized `decay_score` or `computeDecayScore()` after FTS/semantic candidate generation (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:545-550`). Recall also mutates access telemetry by updating `last_used_at`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count`, and `first_recalled_at` for returned ids (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:552-560`).\n11: \n12: Decay is fixed half-life based: importance 5 is infinite, 4 is 180 days, 3 is 90, 2 is 30, 1 is 14; score is `importance × confidence × 0.5^(days_since/half_life)` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:200-227`). Below `0.25`, memories can be soft-deprecated unless protected by importance 5 or `confirm_count >= 5` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:209-210`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:247-260`).\n13: \n14: The explainer is deterministic and side-effect-free. It computes `totalScore = fts*0.40 + semantic*0.35 + importance*0.15 + recency*0.10`, or assigns 75% to the available retrieval channel when only FTS or semantic exists (`packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:1-9`, `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:57-66`). It also emits `importanceBoost`, 90-day linear `recencyBoost`, and a temperature bucket: hot at `recallCount >= 10` or recalled within 7 days, warm at `>=3` or 30 days, cool at `>=1` or 90 days (`packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:30-43`, `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:45-75`). `recall()` attaches this explainer after sorting (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:570-580`).\n15: \n16: `categorise.ts` is a content/category classifier, not verified as a recall query router. It scores six memory categories by regex keyword hits, uses best-hits/total-hits as confidence, accepts the heuristic at threshold `0.6`, otherwise calls Anthropic Haiku with the first 500 chars; on failure it returns the best heuristic guess (`packages/openltm-core/src/recall/categorise.ts:21-78`, `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/categorise.ts:86-138`). UNKNOWN whether any recall path consumes it; scoped source shows it exported as a utility (`packages/openltm-core/src/index.ts:40-42`).\n17: \n18: The docs describe the intended posture as FTS5 BM25 primary, semantic fallback when FTS returns `< 3`, merge/dedup, then decay plus importance boost (`docs/03-architecture.md:472-483`). That conflicts with code, where fallback threshold is `< limit`, default `10` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:417-420`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:444-445`). Verdict: OpenLTM’s posture is better than pure trigger-first for ad-hoc paraphrased recall, but not better than system-spec-kit’s full fused search; the transferable gap is explainability and deficit-triggered rescue.\n19: \n20: ## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n21: - **Claim** · Add a first-class `why_ranked` score breakdown, but derive it from the actual fused ranking pipeline. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:5-9`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:570-580` · **Maps-to** · `memory_search(includeTrace/profile=debug)` · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.94 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user debuggability improves trust, but system-spec-kit should expose vector/BM25/FTS/graph/trigger/FSRS contributions rather than OpenLTM’s four-factor formula.\n22: - **Claim** · Use lexical/trigger deficit detection as a rescue trigger: if candidates are below target N, backfill semantic candidates before returning. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:444-456`, `packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:261-301` · **Maps-to** · `memory_match_triggers`, `memory_quick_search` · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.87 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · It patches trigger-first paraphrase misses without replacing system-spec-kit’s stronger fused retrieval path.\n23: - **Claim** · Do not copy OpenLTM’s current blended score as ranking until ranking and explanation are the same computation. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:57-66`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:545-550` · **Maps-to** · new sub-packet · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · HIGH · **Confidence** · 0.96 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Post-hoc scores that do not order results would poison feedback reducers and make recall failures harder to diagnose.\n24: - **Claim** · Keep FSRS decay instead of OpenLTM’s fixed importance half-life model. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:200-227`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:247-260` · **Maps-to** · FSRS tier/state scoring · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.93 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our FSRS/review-history model already supersedes fixed half-lives for local continuity memory.\n25: - **Claim** · Borrow the local heuristic category classifier shape, but not the cloud LLM fallback as a default. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/categorise.ts:21-78`, `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/categorise.ts:86-138` · **Maps-to** · `memory_save` metadata and context-type inference · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.80 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Heuristics help low-friction classification; Anthropic fallback conflicts with local/offline posture unless explicitly opt-in.\n26: \n27: ## Negative knowledge\n28: - Do not replace system-spec-kit fused search with OpenLTM’s FTS-primary fallback wholesale; it is a simpler candidate-generation policy, not a superior scoring architecture.\n29: - Do not expose an explanation score that is not the actual rank score.\n30: - Do not downgrade FSRS to fixed half-lives.\n31: - Do not copy the cloud classifier fallback into default local memory.\n32: - Do not quote-and-OR every query token if preserving user FTS operators or phrase intent matters.\n33: \n34: ## Open questions\n35: - Should `memory_match_triggers()` get semantic rescue only when trigger confidence is below threshold, or always when result count is below N?\n36: - What exact `why_ranked` schema should unify vector, BM25/FTS5, trigger, causal, FSRS, importance, recency, and state-tier contributions?\n37: - Should recall explanations feed the existing shadow feedback reducers so bad rankings become debuggable training data?\n38: \n39: DELTA_JSON: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"run\":1,\"iteration\":\"001\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"status\":\"insight\",\"focus\":\"Hybrid recall + blended scoring + explainability\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.7,\"findingsCount\":5,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: Add a first-class `why_ranked` score breakdown, but derive it from the actual fused ranking pipeline.\",\"ADAPT: Use lexical/trigger deficit detection as a rescue trigger: if candidates are below target N, backfill semantic candidates before returning.\",\"REJECT: Do not copy OpenLTM’s current blended score as ranking until ranking and explanation are the same computation.\"],\"sources\":[\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:425\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:444\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/config.ts:64\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:261\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:464\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:521\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:545\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:552\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:200\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:209\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:247\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:1\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:57\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:30\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:45\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:570\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/recall/categorise.ts:21\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/recall/categorise.ts:86\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/index.ts:40\",\"docs/03-architecture.md:472\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:417\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:5\"],\"tokensTotal\":93394,\"exitCode\":0,\"timestamp\":\"2026-06-08T13:27:33.210Z\",\"sessionId\":\"2026-06-08-010-openltm-teachings\",\"generation\":1}\n\n(End of file - total 39 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 001 — Hybrid recall + blended scoring + explainability\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.70 · **tokens:** 93394 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nOpenLTM recall is lexical-candidate-first. `recall()` tokenizes the query, quotes every token, joins them with `OR`, then runs `memories_fts MATCH ? ORDER BY rank LIMIT 50` against FTS5; it records BM25-ish ranks as `Math.exp(rank)` because SQLite FTS5 rank is negative and closer to zero is better (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:425-442`). If the FTS candidate set is smaller than the requested `limit`, semantic fallback runs when `ltm.semanticFallback !== false`, calling `getSimilarMemories(query, limit * 2, 0.5)` and merging semantic ids/scores into the same id set (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:444-456`, `packages/openltm-core/src/config.ts:64-72`). Semantic search uses sqlite-vec KNN when available, otherwise brute-force cosine over stored embeddings, with a `similarity >= threshold` filter (`packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:261-301`).\n\nThe merged set is filtered by tags, category, project scope, workspace, agent, and `status = 'active'` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:464-510`). The hot path excludes the embedding blob from result rows (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:521-533`). The actual query-result sorter does **not** sort by the explainer’s 40/35/15/10 blended score; it sorts by materialized `decay_score` or `computeDecayScore()` after FTS/semantic candidate generation (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:545-550`). Recall also mutates access telemetry by updating `last_used_at`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count`, and `first_recalled_at` for returned ids (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:552-560`).\n\nDecay is fixed half-life based: importance 5 is infinite, 4 is 180 days, 3 is 90, 2 is 30, 1 is 14; score is `importance × confidence × 0.5^(days_since/half_life)` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:200-227`). Below `0.25`, memories can be soft-deprecated unless protected by importance 5 or `confirm_count >= 5` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:209-210`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:247-260`).\n\nThe explainer is deterministic and side-effect-free. It computes `totalScore = fts*0.40 + semantic*0.35 + importance*0.15 + recency*0.10`, or assigns 75% to the available retrieval channel when only FTS or semantic exists (`packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:1-9`, `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:57-66`). It also emits `importanceBoost`, 90-day linear `recencyBoost`, and a temperature bucket: hot at `recallCount >= 10` or recalled within 7 days, warm at `>=3` or 30 days, cool at `>=1` or 90 days (`packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:30-43`, `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:45-75`). `recall()` attaches this explainer after sorting (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:570-580`).\n\n`categorise.ts` is a content/category classifier, not verified as a recall query router. It scores six memory categories by regex keyword hits, uses best-hits/total-hits as confidence, accepts the heuristic at threshold `0.6`, otherwise calls Anthropic Haiku with the first 500 chars; on failure it returns the best heuristic guess (`packages/openltm-core/src/recall/categorise.ts:21-78`, `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/categorise.ts:86-138`). UNKNOWN whether any recall path consumes it; scoped source shows it exported as a utility (`packages/openltm-core/src/index.ts:40-42`).\n\nThe docs describe the intended posture as FTS5 BM25 primary, semantic fallback when FTS returns `< 3`, merge/dedup, then decay plus importance boost (`docs/03-architecture.md:472-483`). That conflicts with code, where fallback threshold is `< limit`, default `10` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:417-420`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:444-445`). Verdict: OpenLTM’s posture is better than pure trigger-first for ad-hoc paraphrased recall, but not better than system-spec-kit’s full fused search; the transferable gap is explainability and deficit-triggered rescue.\n\n## Teachings for system-spec-kit","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-001.md","text":"# Iteration 001 — Hybrid recall + blended scoring + explainability\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.70 · **tokens:** 93394 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nOpenLTM recall is lexical-candidate-first. `recall()` tokenizes the query, quotes every token, joins them with `OR`, then runs `memories_fts MATCH ? ORDER BY rank LIMIT 50` against FTS5; it records BM25-ish ranks as `Math.exp(rank)` because SQLite FTS5 rank is negative and closer to zero is better (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:425-442`). If the FTS candidate set is smaller than the requested `limit`, semantic fallback runs when `ltm.semanticFallback !== false`, calling `getSimilarMemories(query, limit * 2, 0.5)` and merging semantic ids/scores into the same id set (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:444-456`, `packages/openltm-core/src/config.ts:64-72`). Semantic search uses sqlite-vec KNN when available, otherwise brute-force cosine over stored embeddings, with a `similarity >= threshold` filter (`packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:261-301`).\n\nThe merged set is filtered by tags, category, project scope, workspace, agent, and `status = 'active'` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:464-510`). The hot path excludes the embedding blob from result rows (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:521-533`). The actual query-result sorter does **not** sort by the explainer’s 40/35/15/10 blended score; it sorts by materialized `decay_score` or `computeDecayScore()` after FTS/semantic candidate generation (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:545-550`). Recall also mutates access telemetry by updating `last_used_at`, `last_recalled_at`, `recall_count`, and `first_recalled_at` for returned ids (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:552-560`).\n\nDecay is fixed half-life based: importance 5 is infinite, 4 is 180 days, 3 is 90, 2 is 30, 1 is 14; score is `importance × confidence × 0.5^(days_since/half_life)` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:200-227`). Below `0.25`, memories can be soft-deprecated unless protected by importance 5 or `confirm_count >= 5` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:209-210`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:247-260`).\n\nThe explainer is deterministic and side-effect-free. It computes `totalScore = fts*0.40 + semantic*0.35 + importance*0.15 + recency*0.10`, or assigns 75% to the available retrieval channel when only FTS or semantic exists (`packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:1-9`, `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:57-66`). It also emits `importanceBoost`, 90-day linear `recencyBoost`, and a temperature bucket: hot at `recallCount >= 10` or recalled within 7 days, warm at `>=3` or 30 days, cool at `>=1` or 90 days (`packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:30-43`, `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:45-75`). `recall()` attaches this explainer after sorting (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:570-580`).\n\n`categorise.ts` is a content/category classifier, not verified as a recall query router. It scores six memory categories by regex keyword hits, uses best-hits/total-hits as confidence, accepts the heuristic at threshold `0.6`, otherwise calls Anthropic Haiku with the first 500 chars; on failure it returns the best heuristic guess (`packages/openltm-core/src/recall/categorise.ts:21-78`, `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/categorise.ts:86-138`). UNKNOWN whether any recall path consumes it; scoped source shows it exported as a utility (`packages/openltm-core/src/index.ts:40-42`).\n\nThe docs describe the intended posture as FTS5 BM25 primary, semantic fallback when FTS returns `< 3`, merge/dedup, then decay plus importance boost (`docs/03-architecture.md:472-483`). That conflicts with code, where fallback threshold is `< limit`, default `10` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:417-420`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:444-445`). Verdict: OpenLTM’s posture is better than pure trigger-first for ad-hoc paraphrased recall, but not better than system-spec-kit’s full fused search; the transferable gap is explainability and deficit-triggered rescue.\n\n## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n- **Claim** · Add a first-class `why_ranked` score breakdown, but derive it from the actual fused ranking pipeline. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:5-9`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:570-580` · **Maps-to** · `memory_search(includeTrace/profile=debug)` · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.94 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user debuggability improves trust, but system-spec-kit should expose vector/BM25/FTS/graph/trigger/FSRS contributions rather than OpenLTM’s four-factor formula.\n- **Claim** · Use lexical/trigger deficit detection as a rescue trigger: if candidates are below target N, backfill semantic candidates before returning. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:444-456`, `packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:261-301` · **Maps-to** · `memory_match_triggers`, `memory_quick_search` · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.87 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · It patches trigger-first paraphrase misses without replacing system-spec-kit’s stronger fused retrieval path.\n- **Claim** · Do not copy OpenLTM’s current blended score as ranking until ranking and explanation are the same computation. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:57-66`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:545-550` · **Maps-to** · new sub-packet · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · HIGH · **Confidence** · 0.96 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Post-hoc scores that do not order results would poison feedback reducers and make recall failures harder to diagnose.\n- **Claim** · Keep FSRS decay instead of OpenLTM’s fixed importance half-life model. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:200-227`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:247-260` · **Maps-to** · FSRS tier/state scoring · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.93 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our FSRS/review-history model already supersedes fixed half-lives for local continuity memory.\n- **Claim** · Borrow the local heuristic category classifier shape, but not the cloud LLM fallback as a default. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/categorise.ts:21-78`, `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/categorise.ts:86-138` · **Maps-to** · `memory_save` metadata and context-type inference · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.80 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Heuristics help low-friction classification; Anthropic fallback conflicts with local/offline posture unless explicitly opt-in.\n\n## Negative knowledge\n- Do not replace system-spec-kit fused search with OpenLTM’s FTS-primary fallback wholesale; it is a simpler candidate-generation policy, not a superior scoring architecture.\n- Do not expose an explanation score that is not the actual rank score.\n- Do not downgrade FSRS to fixed half-lives.\n- Do not copy the cloud classifier fallback into default local memory.\n- Do not quote-and-OR every query token if preserving user FTS operators or phrase intent matters.\n\n## Open questions\n- Should `memory_match_triggers()` get semantic rescue only when trigger confidence is below threshold, or always when result count is below N?\n- What exact `why_ranked` schema should unify vector, BM25/FTS5, trigger, causal, FSRS, importance, recency, and state-tier contributions?\n- Should recall explanations feed the existing shadow feedback reducers so bad rankings become debuggable training data?\n\nDELTA_JSON: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"run\":1,\"iteration\":\"001\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"status\":\"insight\",\"focus\":\"Hybrid recall + blended scoring + explainability\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.7,\"findingsCount\":5,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: Add a first-class `why_ranked` score breakdown, but derive it from the actual fused ranking pipeline.\",\"ADAPT: Use lexical/trigger deficit detection as a rescue trigger: if candidates are below target N, backfill semantic candidates before returning.\",\"REJECT: Do not copy OpenLTM’s current blended score as ranking until ranking and explanation are the same computation.\"],\"sources\":[\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:425\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:444\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/config.ts:64\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:261\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:464\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:521\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:545\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:552\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:200\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:209\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:247\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:1\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:57\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:30\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:45\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:570\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/recall/categorise.ts:21\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/recall/categorise.ts:86\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/index.ts:40\",\"docs/03-architecture.md:472\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:417\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:5\"],\"tokensTotal\":93394,\"exitCode\":0,\"timestamp\":\"2026-06-08T13:27:33.210Z\",\"sessionId\":\"2026-06-08-010-openltm-teachings\",\"generation\":1}","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":39,"totalLines":39,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-001.md","time":{"start":1780926450464,"end":1780926450526}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_036408d1c76c14fc016a26c7f259d481918ee17400f913ff6b"}},"id":"prt_ea77d0aea001qh2mmCzNWcZo57","sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","messageID":"msg_ea77cc18a001W0nhx4yXBV8BDy"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780926450553,"sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_hwiXSJHUOEZmsEzh1EyP1evx","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-007.md","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-007.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 007 — Provenance + audit chain\n2: \n3: **Status:** insight · **Findings:** 6 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.66 · **tokens:** 95248 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n4: \n5: ---\n6: \n7: ## Mechanism\n8: OpenLTM implements provenance as a separate per-memory chain, not as frontmatter. `memory_provenance` is one-to-many, cascades with the memory, and stores `source_type`, `source_ref`, `actor`, `created_at`, and freeform `metadata`; pre-existing rows are backfilled as `legacy` (`migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:1`, `migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:6`, `migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:21`). The actual source taxonomy is `learn`, `git-backfill`, `evaluate-session`, `import-bundle`, `user-promotion`, `janitor-rollup`, `legacy`, so the prompt’s “session” label is not a literal enum value; session is represented indirectly via `source_ref` defaulting to `sessionId` on learn (`migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:9`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:377`).\n9: \n10: Audit is a separate append-oriented mutation log. `memory_audit.memory_id` is intentionally not a foreign key so audit rows survive memory deletion, and each row records `op`, required `actor`, optional `session_id`, `before_json`, `after_json`, and `created_at` (`migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:1`, `migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:6`). The initial op enum is `insert/update/forget/deprecate/supersede/redact/restore`, later rebuilt to add `archive` (`migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:9`, `migrations/014_update_audit_op_check.sql:6`). I did not verify SQL-level immutability triggers; the listed migrations create ordinary tables and indexes.\n11: \n12: The DAO captures slim before/after snapshots that intentionally exclude embeddings, selecting memory metadata, lifecycle timestamps, supersession fields, workspace/agent IDs, and `created_by` (`packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:15`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:18`). `insertProvenance` and `insertAudit` are narrow helpers, while `queryAudit` filters by memory, op, session, and since, ordered newest-first with a default limit of 50 (`packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:27`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:61`).\n13: \n14: Write paths use the audit/provenance layer selectively: duplicate reinforcement snapshots before/after and writes an `update` audit (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:321`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:334`); new learns write `created_by`, a provenance row, and an `insert` audit (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:352`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:377`); forget snapshots before deletion and writes a `forget` audit with `after_json=null` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:606`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:611`). Janitor archive preserves full memory JSON in `memory_archive`, writes an `archive` audit, then deletes the memory (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:45`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:53`). Audit writes are best-effort: `tryAudit` catches and logs failures without rolling back the primary mutation (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:132`).\n15: \n16: Recall can optionally carry provenance. When `includeProvenance` is set, OpenLTM batch-fetches provenance rows for all returned IDs to avoid N+1 queries and attaches them to each memory (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:563`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:89`). The architecture narrative frames this as fixing “what, but not where it came from” and “who/what wrote this?” gaps (`docs/03-architecture.md:710`, `docs/03-architecture.md:727`). It also sketches future replay/diff use cases from the audit log (`docs/03-architecture.md:908`).\n17: \n18: ## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n19: - **Claim** · Add an enum-like provenance source kind per indexed memory, separate from freeform governed provenance strings. · **Evidence** · `migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:9`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:377` · **Maps-to** · `memory_index` / `memory_save` / `memory_index_scan` · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.90 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our single-user store does not need tenant-scale governance, but a stable source-kind taxonomy would make continuity/frontmatter-origin, scan backfills, imports, promotions, and janitor writes auditable without parsing prose.\n20: - **Claim** · Surface provenance on retrieval only when requested, using batch lookup rather than joining it into every search. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:563`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:93` · **Maps-to** · `memory_search(includeTrace)` / `memory_context(includeTrace)` · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.88 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · This complements our provenance-rich envelopes and keeps normal retrieval lean while giving debugging sessions exact source lineage.\n21: - **Claim** · Keep audit snapshots slim and exclude vector payloads. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:15`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:18` · **Maps-to** · `memory_history` / mutation ledger payloads · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.92 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our vector store is separate, so auditing metadata/text deltas without embeddings avoids huge rows and preserves replay/debug utility.\n22: - **Claim** · Preserve deletion audit rows independently from the deleted memory record. · **Evidence** · `migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:1`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:5` · **Maps-to** · `memory_delete`, `memory_bulk_delete`, retention sweep audit · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.84 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our history/mutation ledger already covers lifecycle events, but deletion lineage should survive cleanup as a tombstone/audit class, not be treated like ordinary orphaned child data.\n23: - **Claim** · Do not copy fail-open auditing for governed or canonical continuity writes. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:132`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:386` · **Maps-to** · governance audit / mutation ledger transaction policy · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.95 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Best-effort audit is acceptable for a lightweight plugin, but system-spec-kit already treats mutation integrity and governed ingest as stronger invariants.\n24: - **Claim** · Time-travel replay from audit is interesting but not the immediate delta. · **Evidence** · `docs/03-architecture.md:908`, `docs/03-architecture.md:916` · **Maps-to** · new sub-packet · **Verdict** · DEFER · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.75 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · FSRS, causal edges, active projections, and spec-folder continuity already cover most recovery needs; replay/diff is useful only after source-kind and tombstone audit are normalized.\n25: \n26: ## Negative knowledge\n27: - Do not copy OpenLTM’s taxonomy verbatim: its schema says `learn`, not `session`, and mixes mechanism (`learn`) with origin (`git-backfill`) and lifecycle actor (`janitor-rollup`).\n28: - Do not copy fail-open audit writes for canonical or governed mutations; audit loss should be explicit where compliance/debuggability matters.\n29: - Do not treat comments saying “append-only” as enforcement; without immutability triggers or restricted write paths, this is convention plus DAO discipline.\n30: - Do not duplicate our existing FSRS/causal-edge lifecycle model with OpenLTM’s lighter audit trail; use provenance/audit to explain mutations, not to replace ranking or causal lineage.\n31: \n32: ## Open questions\n33: - Should system-spec-kit use a strict enum for `provenance_source_kind`, or a small controlled vocabulary plus freeform `provenance_source` for compatibility?\n34: - Should deletion audit rows live in `memory_history`, mutation ledger, or a new tombstone-only table?\n35: - Should `includeTrace` expose source-kind provenance by default for canonical continuity rows, or only under debug/research profiles?\n36: \n37: DELTA_JSON: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"run\":1,\"iteration\":\"007\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"status\":\"insight\",\"focus\":\"Provenance + audit chain\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.66,\"findingsCount\":6,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: Add an enum-like provenance source kind per indexed memory, separate from freeform governed provenance strings.\",\"ADOPT: Surface provenance on retrieval only when requested, using batch lookup rather than joining it into every search.\",\"ADOPT: Keep audit snapshots slim and exclude vector payloads.\"],\"sources\":[\"migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:1\",\"migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:6\",\"migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:21\",\"migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:9\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:377\",\"migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:1\",\"migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:6\",\"migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:9\",\"migrations/014_update_audit_op_check.sql:6\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:15\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:18\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:27\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:61\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:321\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:334\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:352\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:606\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:611\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:45\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:53\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:132\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:563\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:89\",\"docs/03-architecture.md:710\",\"docs/03-architecture.md:727\",\"docs/03-architecture.md:908\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:93\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:5\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:386\",\"docs/03-architecture.md:916\"],\"tokensTotal\":95248,\"exitCode\":0,\"timestamp\":\"2026-06-08T13:39:12.502Z\",\"sessionId\":\"2026-06-08-010-openltm-teachings\",\"generation\":1}\n\n(End of file - total 37 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 007 — Provenance + audit chain\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 6 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.66 · **tokens:** 95248 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nOpenLTM implements provenance as a separate per-memory chain, not as frontmatter. `memory_provenance` is one-to-many, cascades with the memory, and stores `source_type`, `source_ref`, `actor`, `created_at`, and freeform `metadata`; pre-existing rows are backfilled as `legacy` (`migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:1`, `migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:6`, `migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:21`). The actual source taxonomy is `learn`, `git-backfill`, `evaluate-session`, `import-bundle`, `user-promotion`, `janitor-rollup`, `legacy`, so the prompt’s “session” label is not a literal enum value; session is represented indirectly via `source_ref` defaulting to `sessionId` on learn (`migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:9`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:377`).\n\nAudit is a separate append-oriented mutation log. `memory_audit.memory_id` is intentionally not a foreign key so audit rows survive memory deletion, and each row records `op`, required `actor`, optional `session_id`, `before_json`, `after_json`, and `created_at` (`migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:1`, `migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:6`). The initial op enum is `insert/update/forget/deprecate/supersede/redact/restore`, later rebuilt to add `archive` (`migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:9`, `migrations/014_update_audit_op_check.sql:6`). I did not verify SQL-level immutability triggers; the listed migrations create ordinary tables and indexes.\n\nThe DAO captures slim before/after snapshots that intentionally exclude embeddings, selecting memory metadata, lifecycle timestamps, supersession fields, workspace/agent IDs, and `created_by` (`packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:15`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:18`). `insertProvenance` and `insertAudit` are narrow helpers, while `queryAudit` filters by memory, op, session, and since, ordered newest-first with a default limit of 50 (`packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:27`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:61`).\n\nWrite paths use the audit/provenance layer selectively: duplicate reinforcement snapshots before/after and writes an `update` audit (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:321`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:334`); new learns write `created_by`, a provenance row, and an `insert` audit (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:352`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:377`); forget snapshots before deletion and writes a `forget` audit with `after_json=null` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:606`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:611`). Janitor archive preserves full memory JSON in `memory_archive`, writes an `archive` audit, then deletes the memory (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:45`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:53`). Audit writes are best-effort: `tryAudit` catches and logs failures without rolling back the primary mutation (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:132`).\n\nRecall can optionally carry provenance. When `includeProvenance` is set, OpenLTM batch-fetches provenance rows for all returned IDs to avoid N+1 queries and attaches them to each memory (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:563`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:89`). The architecture narrative frames this as fixing “what, but not where it came from” and “who/what wrote this?” gaps (`docs/03-architecture.md:710`, `docs/03-architecture.md:727`). It also sketches future replay/diff use cases from the audit log (`docs/03-architecture.md:908`).\n\n## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n- **Claim** · Add an enum-like provenance source kind per indexed memory, separate from freeform governed provenance strings. · **Evidence** · `migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:9`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:377` · **Maps-to** · `memory_index` / `memory_save` / `memory_index_scan` · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.90 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our single-user store does not need tenant-scale governance, but a stable source-kind taxonomy would make continuity/frontmatter-origin, scan backfills, imports, promotions, and janitor writes auditable without parsing prose.\n- **Claim** · Surface provenance on retrieval only when requested, using batch lookup rather than joining it into every search. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:563`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:93` · **Maps-to** · `memory_search(includeTrace)` / `memory_context(includeTrace)` · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.88 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · This complements our provenance-rich envelopes and keeps normal retrieval lean while giving debugging sessions exact source lineage.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-007.md","text":"# Iteration 007 — Provenance + audit chain\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 6 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.66 · **tokens:** 95248 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nOpenLTM implements provenance as a separate per-memory chain, not as frontmatter. `memory_provenance` is one-to-many, cascades with the memory, and stores `source_type`, `source_ref`, `actor`, `created_at`, and freeform `metadata`; pre-existing rows are backfilled as `legacy` (`migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:1`, `migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:6`, `migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:21`). The actual source taxonomy is `learn`, `git-backfill`, `evaluate-session`, `import-bundle`, `user-promotion`, `janitor-rollup`, `legacy`, so the prompt’s “session” label is not a literal enum value; session is represented indirectly via `source_ref` defaulting to `sessionId` on learn (`migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:9`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:377`).\n\nAudit is a separate append-oriented mutation log. `memory_audit.memory_id` is intentionally not a foreign key so audit rows survive memory deletion, and each row records `op`, required `actor`, optional `session_id`, `before_json`, `after_json`, and `created_at` (`migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:1`, `migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:6`). The initial op enum is `insert/update/forget/deprecate/supersede/redact/restore`, later rebuilt to add `archive` (`migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:9`, `migrations/014_update_audit_op_check.sql:6`). I did not verify SQL-level immutability triggers; the listed migrations create ordinary tables and indexes.\n\nThe DAO captures slim before/after snapshots that intentionally exclude embeddings, selecting memory metadata, lifecycle timestamps, supersession fields, workspace/agent IDs, and `created_by` (`packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:15`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:18`). `insertProvenance` and `insertAudit` are narrow helpers, while `queryAudit` filters by memory, op, session, and since, ordered newest-first with a default limit of 50 (`packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:27`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:61`).\n\nWrite paths use the audit/provenance layer selectively: duplicate reinforcement snapshots before/after and writes an `update` audit (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:321`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:334`); new learns write `created_by`, a provenance row, and an `insert` audit (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:352`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:377`); forget snapshots before deletion and writes a `forget` audit with `after_json=null` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:606`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:611`). Janitor archive preserves full memory JSON in `memory_archive`, writes an `archive` audit, then deletes the memory (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:45`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:53`). Audit writes are best-effort: `tryAudit` catches and logs failures without rolling back the primary mutation (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:132`).\n\nRecall can optionally carry provenance. When `includeProvenance` is set, OpenLTM batch-fetches provenance rows for all returned IDs to avoid N+1 queries and attaches them to each memory (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:563`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:89`). The architecture narrative frames this as fixing “what, but not where it came from” and “who/what wrote this?” gaps (`docs/03-architecture.md:710`, `docs/03-architecture.md:727`). It also sketches future replay/diff use cases from the audit log (`docs/03-architecture.md:908`).\n\n## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n- **Claim** · Add an enum-like provenance source kind per indexed memory, separate from freeform governed provenance strings. · **Evidence** · `migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:9`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:377` · **Maps-to** · `memory_index` / `memory_save` / `memory_index_scan` · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.90 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our single-user store does not need tenant-scale governance, but a stable source-kind taxonomy would make continuity/frontmatter-origin, scan backfills, imports, promotions, and janitor writes auditable without parsing prose.\n- **Claim** · Surface provenance on retrieval only when requested, using batch lookup rather than joining it into every search. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:563`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:93` · **Maps-to** · `memory_search(includeTrace)` / `memory_context(includeTrace)` · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.88 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · This complements our provenance-rich envelopes and keeps normal retrieval lean while giving debugging sessions exact source lineage.\n- **Claim** · Keep audit snapshots slim and exclude vector payloads. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:15`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:18` · **Maps-to** · `memory_history` / mutation ledger payloads · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.92 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our vector store is separate, so auditing metadata/text deltas without embeddings avoids huge rows and preserves replay/debug utility.\n- **Claim** · Preserve deletion audit rows independently from the deleted memory record. · **Evidence** · `migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:1`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:5` · **Maps-to** · `memory_delete`, `memory_bulk_delete`, retention sweep audit · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.84 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our history/mutation ledger already covers lifecycle events, but deletion lineage should survive cleanup as a tombstone/audit class, not be treated like ordinary orphaned child data.\n- **Claim** · Do not copy fail-open auditing for governed or canonical continuity writes. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:132`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:386` · **Maps-to** · governance audit / mutation ledger transaction policy · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.95 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Best-effort audit is acceptable for a lightweight plugin, but system-spec-kit already treats mutation integrity and governed ingest as stronger invariants.\n- **Claim** · Time-travel replay from audit is interesting but not the immediate delta. · **Evidence** · `docs/03-architecture.md:908`, `docs/03-architecture.md:916` · **Maps-to** · new sub-packet · **Verdict** · DEFER · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.75 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · FSRS, causal edges, active projections, and spec-folder continuity already cover most recovery needs; replay/diff is useful only after source-kind and tombstone audit are normalized.\n\n## Negative knowledge\n- Do not copy OpenLTM’s taxonomy verbatim: its schema says `learn`, not `session`, and mixes mechanism (`learn`) with origin (`git-backfill`) and lifecycle actor (`janitor-rollup`).\n- Do not copy fail-open audit writes for canonical or governed mutations; audit loss should be explicit where compliance/debuggability matters.\n- Do not treat comments saying “append-only” as enforcement; without immutability triggers or restricted write paths, this is convention plus DAO discipline.\n- Do not duplicate our existing FSRS/causal-edge lifecycle model with OpenLTM’s lighter audit trail; use provenance/audit to explain mutations, not to replace ranking or causal lineage.\n\n## Open questions\n- Should system-spec-kit use a strict enum for `provenance_source_kind`, or a small controlled vocabulary plus freeform `provenance_source` for compatibility?\n- Should deletion audit rows live in `memory_history`, mutation ledger, or a new tombstone-only table?\n- Should `includeTrace` expose source-kind provenance by default for canonical continuity rows, or only under debug/research profiles?\n\nDELTA_JSON: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"run\":1,\"iteration\":\"007\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"status\":\"insight\",\"focus\":\"Provenance + audit chain\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.66,\"findingsCount\":6,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: Add an enum-like provenance source kind per indexed memory, separate from freeform governed provenance strings.\",\"ADOPT: Surface provenance on retrieval only when requested, using batch lookup rather than joining it into every search.\",\"ADOPT: Keep audit snapshots slim and exclude vector payloads.\"],\"sources\":[\"migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:1\",\"migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:6\",\"migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:21\",\"migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:9\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:377\",\"migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:1\",\"migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:6\",\"migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:9\",\"migrations/014_update_audit_op_check.sql:6\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:15\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:18\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:27\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:61\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:321\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:334\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:352\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:606\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:611\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:45\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:53\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:132\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:563\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:89\",\"docs/03-architecture.md:710\",\"docs/03-architecture.md:727\",\"docs/03-architecture.md:908\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:93\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:5\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:386\",\"docs/03-architecture.md:916\"],\"tokensTotal\":95248,\"exitCode\":0,\"timestamp\":\"2026-06-08T13:39:12.502Z\",\"sessionId\":\"2026-06-08-010-openltm-teachings\",\"generation\":1}","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":37,"totalLines":37,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-007.md","time":{"start":1780926450498,"end":1780926450528}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_036408d1c76c14fc016a26c7f25a4081918345822900457e1f"}},"id":"prt_ea77d0b40001sJOeVjmYOLb5n1","sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","messageID":"msg_ea77cc18a001W0nhx4yXBV8BDy"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780926450556,"sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_gxw5gKetIalHR6YtI0VeFiRG","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-002.md","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-002.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 002 — Importance-weighted decay (half-life tiers + materialized decay_score)\n2: \n3: **Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.62 · **tokens:** 91909 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n4: \n5: ---\n6: \n7: ## Mechanism\n8: OpenLTM stores a materialized `decay_score` on `memories`, defaults it to `1.0`, and indexes it descending for relevance-order reads (`migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:4`, `migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:6`). Its janitor refresh is two SQL `UPDATE`s in one transaction: first recompute active-memory scores, then mark low scores deprecated (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:14`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:31`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:40`). The score is `importance × confidence × 0.5^(age/halfLife)`, where `importance=5` and `confirm_count>=10` are non-decaying, importance 4/3/2/else use 180/90/30/14 days, and age is based on `COALESCE(last_used_at, last_confirmed_at, created_at)` (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:16`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:20`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:26`). The docs expose the same half-life table and formula, and say scores below `0.25` are soft-deprecated and not session-start injected (`docs/02-how-it-works.md:58`, `docs/02-how-it-works.md:70`, `docs/02-how-it-works.md:76`). The deprecation SQL enforces `status='active'`, `importance<5`, `confirm_count<10`, and `decay_score<0.25` (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:31`). Recall/query speed is helped because default recall omits the large embedding blob and can `ORDER BY decay_score DESC` in SQL (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:522`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:524`). Access refreshes recency: recall updates `last_used_at`, `last_recalled_at`, and `recall_count`, and the temporal metadata migration adds recall timestamps/counts plus supersession fields (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:552`, `migrations/006_temporal_metadata.sql:3`). Tests exercise the exported formula, including immortal importance 5, decreasing score with age, 180-day half-life for importance 4, and positive nonzero scores (`src/__tests__/decay.test.ts:52`, `src/__tests__/decay.test.ts:76... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n9: \n10: ## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n11: - **Claim** · Materialize a retrieval-decay scalar for hot default paths instead of recomputing every query. · **Evidence** · `migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:524` · **Maps-to** · `memory_search` / vector-index maintenance · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our FSRS SQL is richer, but a maintained `effective_retrievability` cache could speed common ranking if invalidated on access/review/index updates.\n12: - **Claim** · Multiply decay/retrievability by confidence, not only importance. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:17`, `docs/02-how-it-works.md:70` · **Maps-to** · ranking calibration / validation confidence · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.78 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · We already store confidence, but current vector decay uses importance-weighted FSRS; confidence weighting could demote unvalidated memories if not double-counted with quality/feedback scores.\n13: - **Claim** · Add a decay-threshold maintenance action that hides, but does not immediately delete, stale low-value memories. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:31`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:4` · **Maps-to** · deprecated tier / retention sweep / `minState` filters · **Verdict** · DEFER · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.74 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our HOT/WARM/COLD/ARCHIVED and deprecated filters partly cover this; an automatic FSRS-to-deprecated transition needs careful review to avoid hiding valid old decisions.\n14: - **Claim** · Preserve per-memory archive snapshots before janitor deletion. · **Evidence** · `migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:8`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:49` · **Maps-to** · retention/audit subsystem · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.82 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user scale makes this cheap, and it complements checkpoints by making auto-deletion reversible at memory granularity.\n15: - **Claim** · Do not replace FSRS with fixed importance half-lives. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:20`, `src/__tests__/decay.test.ts:94` · **Maps-to** · FSRS scheduler · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · HIGH · **Confidence** · 0.91 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · FSRS already adapts stability from access/review behavior; fixed 14/30/90/180-day buckets are simpler but less personalized.\n16: \n17: ## Negative knowledge\n18: Do not copy hard `confirm_count>=10` immortality; repeated access should increase FSRS stability, not make stale facts permanent.\n19: \n20: Do not copy the apparent deprecated-recall ambiguity; define explicit `includeDeprecated` or `tier=deprecated` semantics.\n21: \n22: Do not copy the parallel JS/SQL threshold drift: exported JS deprecation protects `confirm_count>=5`, while SQL janitor uses `>=10`.\n23: \n24: ## Open questions\n25: Should system-spec-kit materialize `effective_retrievability` only for default/top-level search, or for every retrieval channel?\n26: \n27: Should confidence weighting use `confidence`, `quality_score`, validation count, or learned feedback reducers?\n28: \n29: Should stale FSRS memories become `deprecated`, `DORMANT`, or merely receive lower ranking?\n30: \n31: DELTA_JSON: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"run\":1,\"iteration\":\"002\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"status\":\"insight\",\"focus\":\"Importance-weighted decay (half-life tiers + materialized decay_score)\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.62,\"findingsCount\":5,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: Materialize a retrieval-decay scalar for hot default paths instead of recomputing every query.\",\"ADAPT: Multiply decay/retrievability by confidence, not only importance.\",\"DEFER: Add a decay-threshold maintenance action that hides, but does not immediately delete, stale low-value memories.\"],\"sources\":[\"migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:4\",\"migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:6\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:14\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:31\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:40\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:16\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:20\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:26\",\"docs/02-how-it-works.md:58\",\"docs/02-how-it-works.md:70\",\"docs/02-how-it-works.md:76\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:522\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:524\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:552\",\"migrations/006_temporal_metadata.sql:3\",\"src/__tests__/decay.test.ts:52\",\"src/__tests__/decay.test.ts:76\",\"src/__tests__/decay.test.ts:94\",\"src/__tests__/decay.test.ts:108\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:4\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:49\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:510\",\"migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:5\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:17\",\"migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:8\"],\"tokensTotal\":91909,\"exitCode\":0,\"timestamp\":\"2026-06-08T13:33:08.134Z\",\"sessionId\":\"2026-06-08-010-openltm-teachings\",\"generation\":1}\n\n(End of file - total 31 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 002 — Importance-weighted decay (half-life tiers + materialized decay_score)\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.62 · **tokens:** 91909 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nOpenLTM stores a materialized `decay_score` on `memories`, defaults it to `1.0`, and indexes it descending for relevance-order reads (`migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:4`, `migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:6`). Its janitor refresh is two SQL `UPDATE`s in one transaction: first recompute active-memory scores, then mark low scores deprecated (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:14`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:31`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:40`). The score is `importance × confidence × 0.5^(age/halfLife)`, where `importance=5` and `confirm_count>=10` are non-decaying, importance 4/3/2/else use 180/90/30/14 days, and age is based on `COALESCE(last_used_at, last_confirmed_at, created_at)` (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:16`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:20`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:26`). The docs expose the same half-life table and formula, and say scores below `0.25` are soft-deprecated and not session-start injected (`docs/02-how-it-works.md:58`, `docs/02-how-it-works.md:70`, `docs/02-how-it-works.md:76`). The deprecation SQL enforces `status='active'`, `importance<5`, `confirm_count<10`, and `decay_score<0.25` (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:31`). Recall/query speed is helped because default recall omits the large embedding blob and can `ORDER BY decay_score DESC` in SQL (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:522`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:524`). Access refreshes recency: recall updates `last_used_at`, `last_recalled_at`, and `recall_count`, and the temporal metadata migration adds recall timestamps/counts plus supersession fields (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:552`, `migrations/006_temporal_metadata.sql:3`). Tests exercise the exported formula, including immortal importance 5, decreasing score with age, 180-day half-life for importance 4, and positive nonzero scores (`src/__tests__/decay.test.ts:52`, `src/__tests__/decay.test.ts:76... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n- **Claim** · Materialize a retrieval-decay scalar for hot default paths instead of recomputing every query. · **Evidence** · `migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:524` · **Maps-to** · `memory_search` / vector-index maintenance · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our FSRS SQL is richer, but a maintained `effective_retrievability` cache could speed common ranking if invalidated on access/review/index updates.\n- **Claim** · Multiply decay/retrievability by confidence, not only importance. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:17`, `docs/02-how-it-works.md:70` · **Maps-to** · ranking calibration / validation confidence · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.78 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · We already store confidence, but current vector decay uses importance-weighted FSRS; confidence weighting could demote unvalidated memories if not double-counted with quality/feedback scores.\n- **Claim** · Add a decay-threshold maintenance action that hides, but does not immediately delete, stale low-value memories. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:31`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:4` · **Maps-to** · deprecated tier / retention sweep / `minState` filters · **Verdict** · DEFER · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.74 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our HOT/WARM/COLD/ARCHIVED and deprecated filters partly cover this; an automatic FSRS-to-deprecated transition needs careful review to avoid hiding valid old decisions.\n- **Claim** · Preserve per-memory archive snapshots before janitor deletion. · **Evidence** · `migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:8`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:49` · **Maps-to** · retention/audit subsystem · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.82 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user scale makes this cheap, and it complements checkpoints by making auto-deletion reversible at memory granularity.\n- **Claim** · Do not replace FSRS with fixed importance half-lives. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:20`, `src/__tests__/decay.test.ts:94` · **Maps-to** · FSRS scheduler · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · HIGH · **Confidence** · 0.91 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · FSRS already adapts stability from access/review behavior; fixed 14/30/90/180-day buckets are simpler but less personalized.\n\n## Negative knowledge\nDo not copy hard `confirm_count>=10` immortality; repeated access should increase FSRS stability, not make stale facts permanent.\n\nDo not copy the apparent deprecated-recall ambiguity; define explicit `includeDeprecated` or `tier=deprecated` semantics.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-002.md","text":"# Iteration 002 — Importance-weighted decay (half-life tiers + materialized decay_score)\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.62 · **tokens:** 91909 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nOpenLTM stores a materialized `decay_score` on `memories`, defaults it to `1.0`, and indexes it descending for relevance-order reads (`migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:4`, `migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:6`). Its janitor refresh is two SQL `UPDATE`s in one transaction: first recompute active-memory scores, then mark low scores deprecated (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:14`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:31`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:40`). The score is `importance × confidence × 0.5^(age/halfLife)`, where `importance=5` and `confirm_count>=10` are non-decaying, importance 4/3/2/else use 180/90/30/14 days, and age is based on `COALESCE(last_used_at, last_confirmed_at, created_at)` (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:16`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:20`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:26`). The docs expose the same half-life table and formula, and say scores below `0.25` are soft-deprecated and not session-start injected (`docs/02-how-it-works.md:58`, `docs/02-how-it-works.md:70`, `docs/02-how-it-works.md:76`). The deprecation SQL enforces `status='active'`, `importance<5`, `confirm_count<10`, and `decay_score<0.25` (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:31`). Recall/query speed is helped because default recall omits the large embedding blob and can `ORDER BY decay_score DESC` in SQL (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:522`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:524`). Access refreshes recency: recall updates `last_used_at`, `last_recalled_at`, and `recall_count`, and the temporal metadata migration adds recall timestamps/counts plus supersession fields (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:552`, `migrations/006_temporal_metadata.sql:3`). Tests exercise the exported formula, including immortal importance 5, decreasing score with age, 180-day half-life for importance 4, and positive nonzero scores (`src/__tests__/decay.test.ts:52`, `src/__tests__/decay.test.ts:76... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n- **Claim** · Materialize a retrieval-decay scalar for hot default paths instead of recomputing every query. · **Evidence** · `migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:524` · **Maps-to** · `memory_search` / vector-index maintenance · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our FSRS SQL is richer, but a maintained `effective_retrievability` cache could speed common ranking if invalidated on access/review/index updates.\n- **Claim** · Multiply decay/retrievability by confidence, not only importance. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:17`, `docs/02-how-it-works.md:70` · **Maps-to** · ranking calibration / validation confidence · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.78 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · We already store confidence, but current vector decay uses importance-weighted FSRS; confidence weighting could demote unvalidated memories if not double-counted with quality/feedback scores.\n- **Claim** · Add a decay-threshold maintenance action that hides, but does not immediately delete, stale low-value memories. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:31`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:4` · **Maps-to** · deprecated tier / retention sweep / `minState` filters · **Verdict** · DEFER · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.74 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our HOT/WARM/COLD/ARCHIVED and deprecated filters partly cover this; an automatic FSRS-to-deprecated transition needs careful review to avoid hiding valid old decisions.\n- **Claim** · Preserve per-memory archive snapshots before janitor deletion. · **Evidence** · `migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:8`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:49` · **Maps-to** · retention/audit subsystem · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.82 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user scale makes this cheap, and it complements checkpoints by making auto-deletion reversible at memory granularity.\n- **Claim** · Do not replace FSRS with fixed importance half-lives. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:20`, `src/__tests__/decay.test.ts:94` · **Maps-to** · FSRS scheduler · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · HIGH · **Confidence** · 0.91 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · FSRS already adapts stability from access/review behavior; fixed 14/30/90/180-day buckets are simpler but less personalized.\n\n## Negative knowledge\nDo not copy hard `confirm_count>=10` immortality; repeated access should increase FSRS stability, not make stale facts permanent.\n\nDo not copy the apparent deprecated-recall ambiguity; define explicit `includeDeprecated` or `tier=deprecated` semantics.\n\nDo not copy the parallel JS/SQL threshold drift: exported JS deprecation protects `confirm_count>=5`, while SQL janitor uses `>=10`.\n\n## Open questions\nShould system-spec-kit materialize `effective_retrievability` only for default/top-level search, or for every retrieval channel?\n\nShould confidence weighting use `confidence`, `quality_score`, validation count, or learned feedback reducers?\n\nShould stale FSRS memories become `deprecated`, `DORMANT`, or merely receive lower ranking?\n\nDELTA_JSON: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"run\":1,\"iteration\":\"002\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"status\":\"insight\",\"focus\":\"Importance-weighted decay (half-life tiers + materialized decay_score)\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.62,\"findingsCount\":5,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: Materialize a retrieval-decay scalar for hot default paths instead of recomputing every query.\",\"ADAPT: Multiply decay/retrievability by confidence, not only importance.\",\"DEFER: Add a decay-threshold maintenance action that hides, but does not immediately delete, stale low-value memories.\"],\"sources\":[\"migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:4\",\"migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:6\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:14\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:31\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:40\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:16\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:20\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:26\",\"docs/02-how-it-works.md:58\",\"docs/02-how-it-works.md:70\",\"docs/02-how-it-works.md:76\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:522\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:524\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:552\",\"migrations/006_temporal_metadata.sql:3\",\"src/__tests__/decay.test.ts:52\",\"src/__tests__/decay.test.ts:76\",\"src/__tests__/decay.test.ts:94\",\"src/__tests__/decay.test.ts:108\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:4\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:49\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:510\",\"migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:5\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:17\",\"migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:8\"],\"tokensTotal\":91909,\"exitCode\":0,\"timestamp\":\"2026-06-08T13:33:08.134Z\",\"sessionId\":\"2026-06-08-010-openltm-teachings\",\"generation\":1}","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":31,"totalLines":31,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-002.md","time":{"start":1780926450474,"end":1780926450530}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_036408d1c76c14fc016a26c7f259f48191a956f1af6e30c30a"}},"id":"prt_ea77d0b23001LKH5NzmgpiwSnW","sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","messageID":"msg_ea77cc18a001W0nhx4yXBV8BDy"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780926450557,"sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_tF9dx3FCy1sO25oeTffQwakd","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-004.md","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-004.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 004 — Lifecycle hooks + context-injection envelope\n2: \n3: **Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.66 · **tokens:** 95251 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n4: \n5: ---\n6: \n7: ## Mechanism\n8: \n9: OpenLTM wires five lifecycle surfaces: `SessionStart`, `UpdateContext`, `EvaluateSession`, `PreCompact`, and opt-in `GitCommit`; docs describe startup injection, session-stop progress save, session-stop pattern extraction, compaction snapshotting, and post-commit diff learning (`docs/06-hooks.md:13`, `docs/06-hooks.md:24`, `docs/06-hooks.md:38`). Project identity is resolved by exact registry match, longest prefix, then cwd-derived slug, with fallback context files deciding whether a project is “new” (`hooks/lib/resolveProject.ts:5`, `hooks/lib/resolveProject.ts:118`, `hooks/lib/resolveProject.ts:140`).\n10: \n11: The injection envelope is deliberately bounded. `SessionStart` caps restored summary to 60 lines, LTM memories to 30 lines, conflicts to 5, and ignores summaries older than 30 days (`hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:17`, `hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:20`, `hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:198`). It uses the first 500 chars of `context-summary.md` as semantic query context, retrieves global memories with `minImportance:4, limit:16` and project-scoped memories with `minImportance:2, limit:15`, optionally adds graph insights, then emits a compact status header plus directive, LTM block, conflict block, reminder, and backfill hint (`hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:37`, `hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:52`, `hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:224`, `hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:237`). Core context export also budgets per section: GOAL 10, PROGRESS 20, DEC 15, WATCH 15, using “last lines plus omitted count” truncation (`packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:30`, `packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:39`, `packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:139`).\n12: \n13: `PreCompact` is a durable markdown checkpoint. It first exports from DB, assembling goal/progress/decision/gotcha sections with fixed line budgets, then falls back to the four legacy markdown context files if DB export fails or DB is absent (`hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:12`, `hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:23`, `hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:29`, `hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:39`). It always writes the final snapshot to `context-summary.md` (`hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:56`, `hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:61`).\n14: \n15: `UpdateContext` reconstructs the transcript path, parses JSONL, records either modified files from `Write`/`Edit`/`MultiEdit` or a read-only session line, writes to DB if available, and falls back to trimming `context-progress.md` to 20 lines (`hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:88`, `hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:101`, `hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:116`, `hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:128`, `hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:138`).\n16: \n17: `EvaluateSession` is a candidate-memory extractor, not only a logger. It skips sessions below 5 messages, extracts assistant text capped to the last 8000 chars, captures up to 10 errors and tool counts, writes a daily learned-pattern markdown file, converts up to 3 error blocks into `gotcha` proposals, and optionally asks an LLM for decisions/gotchas/patterns/progress (`hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:20`, `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:98`, `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:146`, `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:190`, `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:219`, `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:223`, `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:240`). The LLM prompt enforces max 5 items per class under 120 chars, and proposal files are JSON with `generatedAt` (`hooks/lib/llmExtract.ts:8`, `hooks/lib/llmExtract.ts:14`, `hooks/lib/proposalQueue.ts:11`, `hooks/lib/proposalQueue.ts:14`).\n18: \n19: `GitCommit` is opt-in backfill. It exits unless `ltm.gitLearnEnabled` is true, skips repos with `.ltmignore`, truncates diffs to 4000 chars, ignores lock/dist/minified patterns, requires a default 200-char post-filter diff, then spawns a detached extractor so git is never blocked (`hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:10`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:24`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:75`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:117`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:132`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:138`). Unlike `EvaluateSession`, commit extraction calls `extractAndLearn` directly with source `git-commit:<hash>` and file tags (`hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:88`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:96`, `hooks/lib/llmExtract.ts:50`, `hooks/lib/llmExtract.ts:61`).\n20: \n21: ## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n22: \n23: - **Claim** · Add a persisted PreCompact markdown snapshot as a low-tech fallback beside the richer hook cache · **Evidence** · `hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:56`, `hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:61` · **Maps-to** · compact hook + spec-folder continuity ladder · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our resume ladder is stronger, but a bounded crash snapshot would cover hook-cache loss without replacing handover/frontmatter.\n24: \n25: - **Claim** · Use fixed per-section line budgets with explicit omitted counts for emergency context envelopes · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:30`, `packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:39`, `packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:142` · **Maps-to** · SessionStart and compaction envelope rendering · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.88 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our token-budgeted retrieval is richer, but line quotas are easier to audit under compaction pressure.\n26: \n27: - **Claim** · Promote transcript-derived discoveries through a proposal queue before durable memory writes · **Evidence** · `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:223`, `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:246`, `hooks/lib/proposalQueue.ts:14` · **Maps-to** · shadow-first learning-feedback reducers · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.82 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our shadow reducers already cover feedback learning, but candidate decision/gotcha proposals could improve recall without silent memory pollution.\n28: \n29: - **Claim** · Consider opt-in git-diff learning backfill, but route it to proposals rather than direct memory writes · **Evidence** · `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:117`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:132`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:138`, `hooks/lib/llmExtract.ts:53` · **Maps-to** · new sub-packet · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · HIGH · **Confidence** · 0.78 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user local fits, but our causal/FSRS store needs provenance review to avoid committing noisy inferred memories.\n30: \n31: - **Claim** · Do not replace spec-folder continuity with OpenLTM’s four context categories · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:16`, `packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:44`, `packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:152` · **Maps-to** · handover.md / implementation-summary continuity frontmatter · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.90 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our canonical docs, causal edges, tiers, and FSRS supersede flat goal/progress/decision/gotcha storage.\n32: \n33: ## Negative knowledge\n34: \n35: Do not copy direct `GitCommit` auto-learn writes; commit diffs are too noisy for our higher-trust causal memory.\n36: \n37: Do not copy the global `~/.claude/projects` context-file topology; system-spec-kit’s packet-local docs are the durable record.\n38: \n39: Do not copy the hard 30-day stale skip as-is; FSRS decay and retrieval state should degrade relevance, not suppress recovery.\n40: \n41: Do not copy dead or unclear knobs: `injectTopN` is read in `SessionStart` but not visibly applied in the scoped source (`hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:211`).\n42: \n43: ## Open questions\n44: \n45: UNKNOWN: where proposal files are reviewed, accepted, or rejected after `EvaluateSession`.\n46: \n47: UNKNOWN: empirical false-positive rate for LLM extraction from transcripts and git diffs.\n48: \n49: Worth synthesis: whether our compact hook should persist a human-readable fallback snapshot into the active spec folder, not only temp hook state.\n50: \n51: DELTA_JSON: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"run\":1,\"iteration\":\"004\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"status\":\"insight\",\"focus\":\"Lifecycle hooks + context-injection envelope\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.66,\"findingsCount\":5,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: Add a persisted PreCompact markdown snapshot as a low-tech fallback beside the richer hook cache\",\"ADAPT: Use fixed per-section line budgets with explicit omitted counts for emergency context envelopes\",\"ADAPT: Promote transcript-derived discoveries through a proposal queue before durable memory writes\"],\"sources\":[\"docs/06-hooks.md:13\",\"docs/06-hooks.md:24\",\"docs/06-hooks.md:38\",\"hooks/lib/resolveProject.ts:5\",\"hooks/lib/resolveProject.ts:118\",\"hooks/lib/resolveProject.ts:140\",\"hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:17\",\"hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:20\",\"hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:198\",\"minImportance:4\",\"minImportance:2\",\"hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:37\",\"hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:52\",\"hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:224\",\"hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:237\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:30\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:39\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:139\",\"hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:12\",\"hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:23\",\"hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:29\",\"hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:39\",\"hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:56\",\"hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:61\",\"hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:88\",\"hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:101\",\"hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:116\",\"hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:128\",\"hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:138\",\"hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:20\",\"hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:98\",\"hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:146\",\"hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:190\",\"hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:219\",\"hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:223\",\"hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:240\",\"hooks/lib/llmExtract.ts:8\",\"hooks/lib/llmExtract.ts:14\",\"hooks/lib/proposalQueue.ts:11\",\"hooks/lib/proposalQueue.ts:14\",\"hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:10\",\"hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:24\",\"hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:75\",\"hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:117\",\"hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:132\",\"hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:138\",\"hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:88\",\"hooks/src/GitCommit.t... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(End of file - total 51 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 004 — Lifecycle hooks + context-injection envelope\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.66 · **tokens:** 95251 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\n\nOpenLTM wires five lifecycle surfaces: `SessionStart`, `UpdateContext`, `EvaluateSession`, `PreCompact`, and opt-in `GitCommit`; docs describe startup injection, session-stop progress save, session-stop pattern extraction, compaction snapshotting, and post-commit diff learning (`docs/06-hooks.md:13`, `docs/06-hooks.md:24`, `docs/06-hooks.md:38`). Project identity is resolved by exact registry match, longest prefix, then cwd-derived slug, with fallback context files deciding whether a project is “new” (`hooks/lib/resolveProject.ts:5`, `hooks/lib/resolveProject.ts:118`, `hooks/lib/resolveProject.ts:140`).\n\nThe injection envelope is deliberately bounded. `SessionStart` caps restored summary to 60 lines, LTM memories to 30 lines, conflicts to 5, and ignores summaries older than 30 days (`hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:17`, `hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:20`, `hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:198`). It uses the first 500 chars of `context-summary.md` as semantic query context, retrieves global memories with `minImportance:4, limit:16` and project-scoped memories with `minImportance:2, limit:15`, optionally adds graph insights, then emits a compact status header plus directive, LTM block, conflict block, reminder, and backfill hint (`hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:37`, `hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:52`, `hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:224`, `hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:237`). Core context export also budgets per section: GOAL 10, PROGRESS 20, DEC 15, WATCH 15, using “last lines plus omitted count” truncation (`packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:30`, `packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:39`, `packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:139`).\n\n`PreCompact` is a durable markdown checkpoint. It first exports from DB, assembling goal/progress/decision/gotcha sections with fixed line budgets, then falls back to the four legacy markdown context files if DB export fails or DB is absent (`hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:12`, `hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:23`, `hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:29`, `hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:39`). It always writes the final snapshot to `context-summary.md` (`hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:56`, `hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:61`).\n\n`UpdateContext` reconstructs the transcript path, parses JSONL, records either modified files from `Write`/`Edit`/`MultiEdit` or a read-only session line, writes to DB if available, and falls back to trimming `context-progress.md` to 20 lines (`hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:88`, `hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:101`, `hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:116`, `hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:128`, `hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:138`).\n\n`EvaluateSession` is a candidate-memory extractor, not only a logger. It skips sessions below 5 messages, extracts assistant text capped to the last 8000 chars, captures up to 10 errors and tool counts, writes a daily learned-pattern markdown file, converts up to 3 error blocks into `gotcha` proposals, and optionally asks an LLM for decisions/gotchas/patterns/progress (`hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:20`, `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:98`, `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:146`, `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:190`, `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:219`, `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:223`, `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:240`). The LLM prompt enforces max 5 items per class under 120 chars, and proposal files are JSON with `generatedAt` (`hooks/lib/llmExtract.ts:8`, `hooks/lib/llmExtract.ts:14`, `hooks/lib/proposalQueue.ts:11`, `hooks/lib/proposalQueue.ts:14`).\n\n`GitCommit` is opt-in backfill. It exits unless `ltm.gitLearnEnabled` is true, skips repos with `.ltmignore`, truncates diffs to 4000 chars, ignores lock/dist/minified patterns, requires a default 200-char post-filter diff, then spawns a detached extractor so git is never blocked (`hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:10`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:24`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:75`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:117`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:132`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:138`). Unlike `EvaluateSession`, commit extraction calls `extractAndLearn` directly with source `git-commit:<hash>` and file tags (`hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:88`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:96`, `hooks/lib/llmExtract.ts:50`, `hooks/lib/llmExtract.ts:61`).\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-004.md","text":"# Iteration 004 — Lifecycle hooks + context-injection envelope\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.66 · **tokens:** 95251 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\n\nOpenLTM wires five lifecycle surfaces: `SessionStart`, `UpdateContext`, `EvaluateSession`, `PreCompact`, and opt-in `GitCommit`; docs describe startup injection, session-stop progress save, session-stop pattern extraction, compaction snapshotting, and post-commit diff learning (`docs/06-hooks.md:13`, `docs/06-hooks.md:24`, `docs/06-hooks.md:38`). Project identity is resolved by exact registry match, longest prefix, then cwd-derived slug, with fallback context files deciding whether a project is “new” (`hooks/lib/resolveProject.ts:5`, `hooks/lib/resolveProject.ts:118`, `hooks/lib/resolveProject.ts:140`).\n\nThe injection envelope is deliberately bounded. `SessionStart` caps restored summary to 60 lines, LTM memories to 30 lines, conflicts to 5, and ignores summaries older than 30 days (`hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:17`, `hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:20`, `hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:198`). It uses the first 500 chars of `context-summary.md` as semantic query context, retrieves global memories with `minImportance:4, limit:16` and project-scoped memories with `minImportance:2, limit:15`, optionally adds graph insights, then emits a compact status header plus directive, LTM block, conflict block, reminder, and backfill hint (`hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:37`, `hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:52`, `hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:224`, `hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:237`). Core context export also budgets per section: GOAL 10, PROGRESS 20, DEC 15, WATCH 15, using “last lines plus omitted count” truncation (`packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:30`, `packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:39`, `packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:139`).\n\n`PreCompact` is a durable markdown checkpoint. It first exports from DB, assembling goal/progress/decision/gotcha sections with fixed line budgets, then falls back to the four legacy markdown context files if DB export fails or DB is absent (`hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:12`, `hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:23`, `hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:29`, `hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:39`). It always writes the final snapshot to `context-summary.md` (`hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:56`, `hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:61`).\n\n`UpdateContext` reconstructs the transcript path, parses JSONL, records either modified files from `Write`/`Edit`/`MultiEdit` or a read-only session line, writes to DB if available, and falls back to trimming `context-progress.md` to 20 lines (`hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:88`, `hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:101`, `hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:116`, `hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:128`, `hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:138`).\n\n`EvaluateSession` is a candidate-memory extractor, not only a logger. It skips sessions below 5 messages, extracts assistant text capped to the last 8000 chars, captures up to 10 errors and tool counts, writes a daily learned-pattern markdown file, converts up to 3 error blocks into `gotcha` proposals, and optionally asks an LLM for decisions/gotchas/patterns/progress (`hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:20`, `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:98`, `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:146`, `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:190`, `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:219`, `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:223`, `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:240`). The LLM prompt enforces max 5 items per class under 120 chars, and proposal files are JSON with `generatedAt` (`hooks/lib/llmExtract.ts:8`, `hooks/lib/llmExtract.ts:14`, `hooks/lib/proposalQueue.ts:11`, `hooks/lib/proposalQueue.ts:14`).\n\n`GitCommit` is opt-in backfill. It exits unless `ltm.gitLearnEnabled` is true, skips repos with `.ltmignore`, truncates diffs to 4000 chars, ignores lock/dist/minified patterns, requires a default 200-char post-filter diff, then spawns a detached extractor so git is never blocked (`hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:10`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:24`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:75`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:117`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:132`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:138`). Unlike `EvaluateSession`, commit extraction calls `extractAndLearn` directly with source `git-commit:<hash>` and file tags (`hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:88`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:96`, `hooks/lib/llmExtract.ts:50`, `hooks/lib/llmExtract.ts:61`).\n\n## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n\n- **Claim** · Add a persisted PreCompact markdown snapshot as a low-tech fallback beside the richer hook cache · **Evidence** · `hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:56`, `hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:61` · **Maps-to** · compact hook + spec-folder continuity ladder · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our resume ladder is stronger, but a bounded crash snapshot would cover hook-cache loss without replacing handover/frontmatter.\n\n- **Claim** · Use fixed per-section line budgets with explicit omitted counts for emergency context envelopes · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:30`, `packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:39`, `packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:142` · **Maps-to** · SessionStart and compaction envelope rendering · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.88 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our token-budgeted retrieval is richer, but line quotas are easier to audit under compaction pressure.\n\n- **Claim** · Promote transcript-derived discoveries through a proposal queue before durable memory writes · **Evidence** · `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:223`, `hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:246`, `hooks/lib/proposalQueue.ts:14` · **Maps-to** · shadow-first learning-feedback reducers · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.82 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our shadow reducers already cover feedback learning, but candidate decision/gotcha proposals could improve recall without silent memory pollution.\n\n- **Claim** · Consider opt-in git-diff learning backfill, but route it to proposals rather than direct memory writes · **Evidence** · `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:117`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:132`, `hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:138`, `hooks/lib/llmExtract.ts:53` · **Maps-to** · new sub-packet · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · HIGH · **Confidence** · 0.78 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user local fits, but our causal/FSRS store needs provenance review to avoid committing noisy inferred memories.\n\n- **Claim** · Do not replace spec-folder continuity with OpenLTM’s four context categories · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:16`, `packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:44`, `packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:152` · **Maps-to** · handover.md / implementation-summary continuity frontmatter · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.90 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our canonical docs, causal edges, tiers, and FSRS supersede flat goal/progress/decision/gotcha storage.\n\n## Negative knowledge\n\nDo not copy direct `GitCommit` auto-learn writes; commit diffs are too noisy for our higher-trust causal memory.\n\nDo not copy the global `~/.claude/projects` context-file topology; system-spec-kit’s packet-local docs are the durable record.\n\nDo not copy the hard 30-day stale skip as-is; FSRS decay and retrieval state should degrade relevance, not suppress recovery.\n\nDo not copy dead or unclear knobs: `injectTopN` is read in `SessionStart` but not visibly applied in the scoped source (`hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:211`).\n\n## Open questions\n\nUNKNOWN: where proposal files are reviewed, accepted, or rejected after `EvaluateSession`.\n\nUNKNOWN: empirical false-positive rate for LLM extraction from transcripts and git diffs.\n\nWorth synthesis: whether our compact hook should persist a human-readable fallback snapshot into the active spec folder, not only temp hook state.\n\nDELTA_JSON: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"run\":1,\"iteration\":\"004\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"status\":\"insight\",\"focus\":\"Lifecycle hooks + context-injection envelope\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.66,\"findingsCount\":5,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: Add a persisted PreCompact markdown snapshot as a low-tech fallback beside the richer hook cache\",\"ADAPT: Use fixed per-section line budgets with explicit omitted counts for emergency context envelopes\",\"ADAPT: Promote transcript-derived discoveries through a proposal queue before durable memory writes\"],\"sources\":[\"docs/06-hooks.md:13\",\"docs/06-hooks.md:24\",\"docs/06-hooks.md:38\",\"hooks/lib/resolveProject.ts:5\",\"hooks/lib/resolveProject.ts:118\",\"hooks/lib/resolveProject.ts:140\",\"hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:17\",\"hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:20\",\"hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:198\",\"minImportance:4\",\"minImportance:2\",\"hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:37\",\"hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:52\",\"hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:224\",\"hooks/src/SessionStart.ts:237\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:30\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:39\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/context.ts:139\",\"hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:12\",\"hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:23\",\"hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:29\",\"hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:39\",\"hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:56\",\"hooks/src/PreCompact.ts:61\",\"hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:88\",\"hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:101\",\"hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:116\",\"hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:128\",\"hooks/src/UpdateContext.ts:138\",\"hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:20\",\"hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:98\",\"hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:146\",\"hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:190\",\"hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:219\",\"hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:223\",\"hooks/src/EvaluateSession.ts:240\",\"hooks/lib/llmExtract.ts:8\",\"hooks/lib/llmExtract.ts:14\",\"hooks/lib/proposalQueue.ts:11\",\"hooks/lib/proposalQueue.ts:14\",\"hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:10\",\"hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:24\",\"hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:75\",\"hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:117\",\"hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:132\",\"hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:138\",\"hooks/src/GitCommit.ts:88\",\"hooks/src/GitCommit.t... (line truncated to 2000 chars)","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":51,"totalLines":51,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-004.md","time":{"start":1780926450489,"end":1780926450532}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_036408d1c76c14fc016a26c7f25a18819194b19d7e1efc367e"}},"id":"prt_ea77d0b37001yPpP9bFuJcElHB","sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","messageID":"msg_ea77cc18a001W0nhx4yXBV8BDy"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780926450557,"sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_vNSQyRU4jLsrSckdgeyLq3x5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-008.md","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-008.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 008 — Embedding provider abstraction + graceful degradation\n2: \n3: **Status:** insight · **Findings:** 6 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.58 · **tokens:** 105685 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n4: \n5: ---\n6: \n7: ## Mechanism\n8: OpenLTM’s runtime embedding abstraction is small and provider-gated: `EmbeddingProviderName` is only `\"gemini\" | \"openai\" | \"ollama\" | \"disabled\"`, with `name`, `model`, `dim`, `available()`, and `generate()` as the provider contract, and the default config is `provider: \"disabled\"` with `confidenceThreshold: 0.6` (`packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:7`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:22`). The factory dynamically loads Gemini/OpenAI/Ollama and falls back to `DisabledProvider` for anything else (`packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:30`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:47`). The disabled provider is a true no-op: `available()` is false and `generate()` returns null (`packages/openltm-core/src/providers/disabled.ts:7`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/disabled.ts:12`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/disabled.ts:16`).\n9: \n10: Provider implementations degrade quietly. Ollama defaults to `nomic-embed-text`, dim `768`, and `http://localhost:11434`; availability probes `/api/tags` with a 2s timeout, and generation catches failures as null (`packages/openltm-core/src/providers/ollama.ts:9`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/ollama.ts:14`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/ollama.ts:18`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/ollama.ts:27`). OpenAI uses dim `1536` and returns null on non-OK responses (`packages/openltm-core/src/providers/openai.ts:9`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/openai.ts:29`). Gemini uses dim `768`, requires an API key, and returns null on non-OK responses (`packages/openltm-core/src/providers/gemini.ts:10`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/gemini.ts:19`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/gemini.ts:31`). `cohere` and `openrouter` are not in the runtime `src/providers` abstraction; they exist in the janitor provider layer, whose type union includes them (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/providers/types.ts:149`).\n11: \n12: Recall is FTS5-first. Query terms are quoted and OR-joined, then searched against `memories_fts` with `ORDER BY rank LIMIT 50`; BM25’s negative rank is normalized with `Math.exp(rank)` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:426`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:433`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:439`). Only when FTS returns fewer IDs than the requested limit does OpenLTM attempt semantic augmentation, guarded by `ltm.semanticFallback !== false`, hard-coded to `threshold = 0.5`, and wrapped in `try/catch` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:444`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:448`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:452`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:457`). If no provider is configured, `embedText()` returns null and semantic search returns `[]` (`packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:191`, `packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:194`, `packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:261`). The explainer states that when semantic is absent, FTS absorbs the semantic weight: `fts * 0.75 + importance * 0.15 + recency * 0.10` (`packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:60`). However, query results are sorted by `decay_score`, not by that explainer score; the explainer is attached after sorting (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:545`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:548`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:570`).\n13: \n14: The split-table migration creates `memory_embeddings(memory_id PRIMARY KEY, embedding BLOB, model, dim, created_at)`, copies non-null legacy blobs from `memories.embedding`, drops the old partial index, and drops the inline column (`migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:5`, `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:16`, `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:21`, `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:25`). Migration 003 was only an inline-embedding presence index (`migrations/003_embedding_index.sql:3`). The DAO writes the side table and dual-writes sqlite-vec when available (`packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:35`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:48`), and recall explicitly selects slim columns to exclude the blob from MCP hot paths (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:522`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:527`). `sqlite-vec` is a derived, lazy, no-throw index over `memory_embeddings`, default dim `768`, with `similarity = 1 - distance`; when unavailable, callers fall back to JS cosine or FTS-only paths (`packages/openltm-core/src/vec/index.ts:4`, `packages/openltm-core/src/vec/index.ts:10`, `packages/openltm-core/src/vec/index.ts:20`, `packages/openltm-core/src/vec/index.ts:93`). UNKNOWN: `docs/04-configuration.md` documents `semanticFallback`, but not the source-level `embeddings` provider block (`docs/04-configuration.md:7`, `docs/04-configuration.md:29`, `packages/openltm-core/src/config.ts:17`).\n15: \n16: ## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n17: - **Claim** · Add a first-class disabled/degraded embedder state without changing the ollama-nomic model · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/disabled.ts:12` · **Maps-to** · `embedder_list`, `memory_search` trace · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.90 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our vector channel can fail locally too; typed degradation would make BM25/FTS/trigger-only behavior explicit rather than accidental.\n18: - **Claim** · Keep embedding payloads out of hot recall/MCP rows and store only model/dim/status metadata beside the index · **Evidence** · `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:522` · **Maps-to** · `memory_index` plus separate vector shard · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · We already avoid inline blobs via a separate vector store, but a small SQL metadata side table could improve reconciliation and traceability.\n19: - **Claim** · Gate semantic fallback by channel availability and lexical result count, not by hard failure · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:444`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:457` · **Maps-to** · `memory_search` fusion/degraded modes · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.82 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our hybrid retrieval is richer, but explicit “vector skipped, lexical sufficient/unavailable” traces would improve operator trust.\n20: - **Claim** · Treat ANN/vector indexes as rebuildable derived surfaces keyed by model and dimension · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/vec/index.ts:108`, `packages/openltm-core/src/vec/index.ts:119` · **Maps-to** · vector shard activation and `memory_embedding_reconcile` · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.88 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · This fits our self-maintaining index and protects ollama-nomic consistency without swapping models.\n21: - **Claim** · Reject OpenLTM’s explainer scoring as a ranking model because it is not actually used for ordering · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:58`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:548` · **Maps-to** · hybrid RRF/FSRS/causal scoring · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.84 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our FSRS and causal-edge design is stronger; copying a display-only score would add confusion.\n22: - **Claim** · Batch provider results should report model, dimensions, and token usage when available · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/providers/types.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/providers/openai.ts:51` · **Maps-to** · embedder telemetry dashboard · **Verdict** · DEFER · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.74 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Useful for diagnostics, but less urgent for local ollama-nomic where cost accounting is not central.\n23: \n24: ## Negative knowledge\n25: - Do not copy provider proliferation as a product goal; system-spec-kit should keep ollama-nomic and abstract availability/degradation around it.\n26: - Do not copy unwired knobs like `confidenceThreshold`; OpenLTM defines it but recall uses a hard-coded `0.5` semantic threshold.\n27: - Do not copy the ranking/explainer split; OpenLTM computes FTS/semantic scores but sorts query results by decay score.\n28: - Do not copy schema drift: fresh `schema.sql` still declares `memories.embedding`, while migration 010 drops it and some older paths still query it.\n29: - Do not copy docs/config drift; requested docs expose `semanticFallback` but not the source-level `embeddings` config block.\n30: \n31: ## Open questions\n32: - Should system-spec-kit add a compact SQL `memory_embeddings` metadata table even though vectors already live in a separate store?\n33: - Should degraded search responses expose “vector unavailable/skipped” in trace output by default?\n34: - Should embedder health be driven by Ollama reachability, vector coverage, or active-shard reconciliation as the canonical signal?\n35: \n36: DELTA_JSON: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"run\":1,\"iteration\":\"008\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"status\":\"insight\",\"focus\":\"Embedding provider abstraction + graceful degradation\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.58,\"findingsCount\":6,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: Add a first-class disabled/degraded embedder state without changing the ollama-nomic model\",\"ADAPT: Keep embedding payloads out of hot recall/MCP rows and store only model/dim/status metadata beside the index\",\"ADAPT: Gate semantic fallback by channel availability and lexical result count, not by hard failure\"],\"sources\":[\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:7\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:17\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:22\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:30\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:47\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/disabled.ts:7\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/disabled.ts:12\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/disabled.ts:16\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/ollama.ts:9\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/ollama.ts:14\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/ollama.ts:18\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/ollama.ts:27\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/openai.ts:9\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/openai.ts:29\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/gemini.ts:10\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/gemini.ts:19\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/gemini.ts:31\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/providers/types.ts:149\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:426\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:433\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:439\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:444\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:448\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:452\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:457\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:191\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:194\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:261\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:5\",\"packages/openltm-c... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(End of file - total 36 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 008 — Embedding provider abstraction + graceful degradation\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 6 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.58 · **tokens:** 105685 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nOpenLTM’s runtime embedding abstraction is small and provider-gated: `EmbeddingProviderName` is only `\"gemini\" | \"openai\" | \"ollama\" | \"disabled\"`, with `name`, `model`, `dim`, `available()`, and `generate()` as the provider contract, and the default config is `provider: \"disabled\"` with `confidenceThreshold: 0.6` (`packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:7`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:22`). The factory dynamically loads Gemini/OpenAI/Ollama and falls back to `DisabledProvider` for anything else (`packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:30`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:47`). The disabled provider is a true no-op: `available()` is false and `generate()` returns null (`packages/openltm-core/src/providers/disabled.ts:7`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/disabled.ts:12`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/disabled.ts:16`).\n\nProvider implementations degrade quietly. Ollama defaults to `nomic-embed-text`, dim `768`, and `http://localhost:11434`; availability probes `/api/tags` with a 2s timeout, and generation catches failures as null (`packages/openltm-core/src/providers/ollama.ts:9`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/ollama.ts:14`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/ollama.ts:18`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/ollama.ts:27`). OpenAI uses dim `1536` and returns null on non-OK responses (`packages/openltm-core/src/providers/openai.ts:9`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/openai.ts:29`). Gemini uses dim `768`, requires an API key, and returns null on non-OK responses (`packages/openltm-core/src/providers/gemini.ts:10`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/gemini.ts:19`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/gemini.ts:31`). `cohere` and `openrouter` are not in the runtime `src/providers` abstraction; they exist in the janitor provider layer, whose type union includes them (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/providers/types.ts:149`).\n\nRecall is FTS5-first. Query terms are quoted and OR-joined, then searched against `memories_fts` with `ORDER BY rank LIMIT 50`; BM25’s negative rank is normalized with `Math.exp(rank)` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:426`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:433`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:439`). Only when FTS returns fewer IDs than the requested limit does OpenLTM attempt semantic augmentation, guarded by `ltm.semanticFallback !== false`, hard-coded to `threshold = 0.5`, and wrapped in `try/catch` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:444`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:448`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:452`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:457`). If no provider is configured, `embedText()` returns null and semantic search returns `[]` (`packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:191`, `packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:194`, `packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:261`). The explainer states that when semantic is absent, FTS absorbs the semantic weight: `fts * 0.75 + importance * 0.15 + recency * 0.10` (`packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:60`). However, query results are sorted by `decay_score`, not by that explainer score; the explainer is attached after sorting (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:545`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:548`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:570`).\n\nThe split-table migration creates `memory_embeddings(memory_id PRIMARY KEY, embedding BLOB, model, dim, created_at)`, copies non-null legacy blobs from `memories.embedding`, drops the old partial index, and drops the inline column (`migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:5`, `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:16`, `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:21`, `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:25`). Migration 003 was only an inline-embedding presence index (`migrations/003_embedding_index.sql:3`). The DAO writes the side table and dual-writes sqlite-vec when available (`packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:35`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:48`), and recall explicitly selects slim columns to exclude the blob from MCP hot paths (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:522`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:527`). `sqlite-vec` is a derived, lazy, no-throw index over `memory_embeddings`, default dim `768`, with `similarity = 1 - distance`; when unavailable, callers fall back to JS cosine or FTS-only paths (`packages/openltm-core/src/vec/index.ts:4`, `packages/openltm-core/src/vec/index.ts:10`, `packages/openltm-core/src/vec/index.ts:20`, `packages/openltm-core/src/vec/index.ts:93`). UNKNOWN: `docs/04-configuration.md` documents `semanticFallback`, but not the source-level `embeddings` provider block (`docs/04-configuration.md:7`, `docs/04-configuration.md:29`, `packages/openltm-core/src/config.ts:17`).\n\n## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n- **Claim** · Add a first-class disabled/degraded embedder state without changing the ollama-nomic model · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/disabled.ts:12` · **Maps-to** · `embedder_list`, `memory_search` trace · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.90 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our vector channel can fail locally too; typed degradation would make BM25/FTS/trigger-only behavior explicit rather than accidental.\n- **Claim** · Keep embedding payloads out of hot recall/MCP rows and store only model/dim/status metadata beside the index · **Evidence** · `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:522` · **Maps-to** · `memory_index` plus separate vector shard · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · We already avoid inline blobs via a separate vector store, but a small SQL metadata side table could improve reconciliation and traceability.\n- **Claim** · Gate semantic fallback by channel availability and lexical result count, not by hard failure · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:444`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:457` · **Maps-to** · `memory_search` fusion/degraded modes · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.82 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our hybrid retrieval is richer, but explicit “vector skipped, lexical sufficient/unavailable” traces would improve operator trust.\n- **Claim** · Treat ANN/vector indexes as rebuildable derived surfaces keyed by model and dimension · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/vec/index.ts:108`, `packages/openltm-core/src/vec/index.ts:119` · **Maps-to** · vector shard activation and `memory_embedding_reconcile` · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.88 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · This fits our self-maintaining index and protects ollama-nomic consistency without swapping models.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-008.md","text":"# Iteration 008 — Embedding provider abstraction + graceful degradation\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 6 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.58 · **tokens:** 105685 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nOpenLTM’s runtime embedding abstraction is small and provider-gated: `EmbeddingProviderName` is only `\"gemini\" | \"openai\" | \"ollama\" | \"disabled\"`, with `name`, `model`, `dim`, `available()`, and `generate()` as the provider contract, and the default config is `provider: \"disabled\"` with `confidenceThreshold: 0.6` (`packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:7`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:22`). The factory dynamically loads Gemini/OpenAI/Ollama and falls back to `DisabledProvider` for anything else (`packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:30`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:47`). The disabled provider is a true no-op: `available()` is false and `generate()` returns null (`packages/openltm-core/src/providers/disabled.ts:7`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/disabled.ts:12`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/disabled.ts:16`).\n\nProvider implementations degrade quietly. Ollama defaults to `nomic-embed-text`, dim `768`, and `http://localhost:11434`; availability probes `/api/tags` with a 2s timeout, and generation catches failures as null (`packages/openltm-core/src/providers/ollama.ts:9`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/ollama.ts:14`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/ollama.ts:18`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/ollama.ts:27`). OpenAI uses dim `1536` and returns null on non-OK responses (`packages/openltm-core/src/providers/openai.ts:9`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/openai.ts:29`). Gemini uses dim `768`, requires an API key, and returns null on non-OK responses (`packages/openltm-core/src/providers/gemini.ts:10`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/gemini.ts:19`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/gemini.ts:31`). `cohere` and `openrouter` are not in the runtime `src/providers` abstraction; they exist in the janitor provider layer, whose type union includes them (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/providers/types.ts:149`).\n\nRecall is FTS5-first. Query terms are quoted and OR-joined, then searched against `memories_fts` with `ORDER BY rank LIMIT 50`; BM25’s negative rank is normalized with `Math.exp(rank)` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:426`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:433`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:439`). Only when FTS returns fewer IDs than the requested limit does OpenLTM attempt semantic augmentation, guarded by `ltm.semanticFallback !== false`, hard-coded to `threshold = 0.5`, and wrapped in `try/catch` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:444`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:448`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:452`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:457`). If no provider is configured, `embedText()` returns null and semantic search returns `[]` (`packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:191`, `packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:194`, `packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:261`). The explainer states that when semantic is absent, FTS absorbs the semantic weight: `fts * 0.75 + importance * 0.15 + recency * 0.10` (`packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:60`). However, query results are sorted by `decay_score`, not by that explainer score; the explainer is attached after sorting (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:545`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:548`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:570`).\n\nThe split-table migration creates `memory_embeddings(memory_id PRIMARY KEY, embedding BLOB, model, dim, created_at)`, copies non-null legacy blobs from `memories.embedding`, drops the old partial index, and drops the inline column (`migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:5`, `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:16`, `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:21`, `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:25`). Migration 003 was only an inline-embedding presence index (`migrations/003_embedding_index.sql:3`). The DAO writes the side table and dual-writes sqlite-vec when available (`packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:35`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:48`), and recall explicitly selects slim columns to exclude the blob from MCP hot paths (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:522`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:527`). `sqlite-vec` is a derived, lazy, no-throw index over `memory_embeddings`, default dim `768`, with `similarity = 1 - distance`; when unavailable, callers fall back to JS cosine or FTS-only paths (`packages/openltm-core/src/vec/index.ts:4`, `packages/openltm-core/src/vec/index.ts:10`, `packages/openltm-core/src/vec/index.ts:20`, `packages/openltm-core/src/vec/index.ts:93`). UNKNOWN: `docs/04-configuration.md` documents `semanticFallback`, but not the source-level `embeddings` provider block (`docs/04-configuration.md:7`, `docs/04-configuration.md:29`, `packages/openltm-core/src/config.ts:17`).\n\n## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n- **Claim** · Add a first-class disabled/degraded embedder state without changing the ollama-nomic model · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/providers/disabled.ts:12` · **Maps-to** · `embedder_list`, `memory_search` trace · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.90 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our vector channel can fail locally too; typed degradation would make BM25/FTS/trigger-only behavior explicit rather than accidental.\n- **Claim** · Keep embedding payloads out of hot recall/MCP rows and store only model/dim/status metadata beside the index · **Evidence** · `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:522` · **Maps-to** · `memory_index` plus separate vector shard · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · We already avoid inline blobs via a separate vector store, but a small SQL metadata side table could improve reconciliation and traceability.\n- **Claim** · Gate semantic fallback by channel availability and lexical result count, not by hard failure · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:444`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:457` · **Maps-to** · `memory_search` fusion/degraded modes · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.82 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our hybrid retrieval is richer, but explicit “vector skipped, lexical sufficient/unavailable” traces would improve operator trust.\n- **Claim** · Treat ANN/vector indexes as rebuildable derived surfaces keyed by model and dimension · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/vec/index.ts:108`, `packages/openltm-core/src/vec/index.ts:119` · **Maps-to** · vector shard activation and `memory_embedding_reconcile` · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.88 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · This fits our self-maintaining index and protects ollama-nomic consistency without swapping models.\n- **Claim** · Reject OpenLTM’s explainer scoring as a ranking model because it is not actually used for ordering · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:58`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:548` · **Maps-to** · hybrid RRF/FSRS/causal scoring · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.84 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our FSRS and causal-edge design is stronger; copying a display-only score would add confusion.\n- **Claim** · Batch provider results should report model, dimensions, and token usage when available · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/providers/types.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/providers/openai.ts:51` · **Maps-to** · embedder telemetry dashboard · **Verdict** · DEFER · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.74 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Useful for diagnostics, but less urgent for local ollama-nomic where cost accounting is not central.\n\n## Negative knowledge\n- Do not copy provider proliferation as a product goal; system-spec-kit should keep ollama-nomic and abstract availability/degradation around it.\n- Do not copy unwired knobs like `confidenceThreshold`; OpenLTM defines it but recall uses a hard-coded `0.5` semantic threshold.\n- Do not copy the ranking/explainer split; OpenLTM computes FTS/semantic scores but sorts query results by decay score.\n- Do not copy schema drift: fresh `schema.sql` still declares `memories.embedding`, while migration 010 drops it and some older paths still query it.\n- Do not copy docs/config drift; requested docs expose `semanticFallback` but not the source-level `embeddings` config block.\n\n## Open questions\n- Should system-spec-kit add a compact SQL `memory_embeddings` metadata table even though vectors already live in a separate store?\n- Should degraded search responses expose “vector unavailable/skipped” in trace output by default?\n- Should embedder health be driven by Ollama reachability, vector coverage, or active-shard reconciliation as the canonical signal?\n\nDELTA_JSON: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"run\":1,\"iteration\":\"008\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"status\":\"insight\",\"focus\":\"Embedding provider abstraction + graceful degradation\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.58,\"findingsCount\":6,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: Add a first-class disabled/degraded embedder state without changing the ollama-nomic model\",\"ADAPT: Keep embedding payloads out of hot recall/MCP rows and store only model/dim/status metadata beside the index\",\"ADAPT: Gate semantic fallback by channel availability and lexical result count, not by hard failure\"],\"sources\":[\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:7\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:17\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:22\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:30\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/embeddingProvider.ts:47\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/disabled.ts:7\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/disabled.ts:12\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/disabled.ts:16\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/ollama.ts:9\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/ollama.ts:14\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/ollama.ts:18\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/ollama.ts:27\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/openai.ts:9\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/openai.ts:29\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/gemini.ts:10\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/gemini.ts:19\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/providers/gemini.ts:31\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/providers/types.ts:149\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:426\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:433\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:439\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:444\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:448\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:452\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:457\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:191\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:194\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:261\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/recall/explainer.ts:5\",\"packages/openltm-c... (line truncated to 2000 chars)","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":36,"totalLines":36,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-008.md","time":{"start":1780926450502,"end":1780926450534}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_036408d1c76c14fc016a26c7f25a4881918688a5f9c594504e"}},"id":"prt_ea77d0b43001EG3vPZ555TusKN","sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","messageID":"msg_ea77cc18a001W0nhx4yXBV8BDy"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780926450557,"sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_5vlJtIy0dDOOgoWOEiFnKBR4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-006.md","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-006.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 006 — Secret redaction before write\n2: \n3: **Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.68 · **tokens:** 107290 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n4: \n5: ---\n6: \n7: ## Mechanism\n8: OpenLTM implements redaction as a fixed ordered `PATTERNS` array of `{id, regex, replacement}` objects, replacing matches with typed placeholders such as `[REDACTED:aws-access-key]` and `[REDACTED:jwt]` (`packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:21`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:62`). The pattern set covers AWS access keys, contextual 40-char AWS secret keys, GitHub tokens, OpenAI/Anthropic/Google/Stripe/Slack tokens, JWTs, bearer tokens, authenticated DB/Redis connection strings, PEM private keys, and generic quoted API-key-like assignments (`packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:18`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:26`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:31`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:36`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:41`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:46`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:56`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:61`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:66`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:71`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:76`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:81`).\n9: \n10: The scrubber is sequential and fail-open: it resets each regex `lastIndex`, applies `replace`, records deduplicated pattern IDs in a `Set`, and returns original text with no redactions if anything throws (`packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:90`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:93`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:96`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:100`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:101`). The write path invokes `scrubSecrets(input.content)` immediately in `learn()`, before deduplication, existing-row lookup, insert, markdown export, embedding enqueue, and auto-relation work (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:304`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:307`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:314`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:317`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:352`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:394`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:401`). It logs only count and pattern IDs, not secret values (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:309`). It derives fallback titles from scrubbed content, but caller-provided `title`, `source`, `project_scope`, and `provenanceMetadata` are not scrubbed in the shown path (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:350`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:361`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:382`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:383`).\n11: \n12: I found no dedicated scrubber test in the scoped `packages/openltm-core/src/__tests__/*`; the files visible there are CLI/install and extension capability tests (`packages/openltm-core/src/__tests__/cli.test.ts:1`, `packages/openltm-core/src/__tests__/extensions.test.ts:1`). In system-spec-kit, direct `memory_save` parses file content and persists `parsed.content` as `contentText` into `memory_index`, while the existing redaction gate is scoped to extracted working-memory summaries and stores only a redaction flag, not redacted content (`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/parsing/memory-parser.ts:244`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/handlers/save/create-record.ts:316`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/vector-index-mutations.ts:301`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/extraction/extraction-adapter.ts:246`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/cognitive/working-memory.ts:449`).\n13: \n14: ## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n15: - **Claim** · Add a pre-index secret scrubber on `memory_save` content before embedding, FTS, BM25, and `content_text` persistence · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:307`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:352`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/handlers/save/create-record.ts:328` · **Maps-to** · `memory_save` ingest pipeline · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.88 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user local storage still leaks secrets into SQLite/vector caches; FSRS/causal/self-maintenance do not mitigate secret persistence.\n16: - **Claim** · Run redaction before dedup/content-hash decisions so two otherwise identical memories differing only by secret value collapse safely · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:307`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:314`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/handlers/memory-save.ts:2521` · **Maps-to** · `checkContentHashDedup` / `computeContentHash` · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.82 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our lineage and causal edges preserve version history, but hashing raw secrets first can still create secret-derived durable identifiers.\n17: - **Claim** · Keep typed redaction markers instead of generic `[REDACTED]` for operator diagnosis without exposing values · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:21`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:37`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/extraction/redaction-gate.ts:61` · **Maps-to** · extraction redaction gate and new memory-save scrubber · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our current generic marker is safer but less auditable; typed categories help tune false positives while preserving local privacy.\n18: - **Claim** · Preserve our high-entropy false-positive exclusions if adopting broader secret patterns · **Evidence** · `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/extraction/redaction-gate.ts:21`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/extraction/redaction-gate.ts:44`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/extraction/redaction-gate.ts:48` · **Maps-to** · new sub-packet · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.84 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · OpenLTM lacks generic high-entropy matching, while our existing exclusions avoid redacting git SHAs and UUIDs.\n19: - **Claim** · Add targeted tests for every secret class and for benign long tokens · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/__tests__/cli.test.ts:1`, `packages/openltm-core/src/__tests__/extensions.test.ts:1`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/tests/redaction-gate.vitest.ts:9` · **Maps-to** · memory-save security tests · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.78 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · We already test extraction redaction; the missing part is write-path persistence coverage.\n20: \n21: ## Negative knowledge\n22: - Do not copy OpenLTM’s fail-open behavior unchanged; returning original text on scrubber failure can persist the exact secret.\n23: - Do not scrub only `content`; titles, trigger phrases, provenance metadata, and routing summaries can also carry secrets.\n24: - Do not copy the broad generic API-key regex without calibration; it can over-redact whole quoted assignment fragments.\n25: - Do not redact emails by default in long-term spec memory unless a privacy policy requires it; project docs often contain legitimate contact identifiers.\n26: \n27: ## Open questions\n28: - Should redacted canonical spec files be rewritten, or should only the indexed `content_text`, embeddings, and FTS rows be scrubbed?\n29: - Should redaction block the save when the redaction ratio is high, matching our extraction skip-threshold pattern?\n30: - Should secret-redaction metadata become searchable/auditable as a governance field without storing matched values?\n31: \n32: DELTA_JSON: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"run\":1,\"iteration\":\"006\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"status\":\"insight\",\"focus\":\"Secret redaction before write\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.68,\"findingsCount\":5,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADOPT: Add a pre-index secret scrubber on `memory_save` content before embedding, FTS, BM25, and `content_text` persistence\",\"ADAPT: Run redaction before dedup/content-hash decisions so two otherwise identical memories differing only by secret value collapse safely\",\"ADAPT: Keep typed redaction markers instead of generic `[REDACTED]` for operator diagnosis without exposing values\"],\"sources\":[\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:17\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:21\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:62\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:18\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:26\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:31\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:36\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:41\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:46\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:51\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:56\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:61\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:66\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:71\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:76\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:81\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:90\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:93\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:96\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:100\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:101\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:304\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:307\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:314\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:317\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:352\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:394\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:401\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:309\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:350\",\"packages/openltm-cor... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(End of file - total 32 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 006 — Secret redaction before write\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.68 · **tokens:** 107290 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nOpenLTM implements redaction as a fixed ordered `PATTERNS` array of `{id, regex, replacement}` objects, replacing matches with typed placeholders such as `[REDACTED:aws-access-key]` and `[REDACTED:jwt]` (`packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:21`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:62`). The pattern set covers AWS access keys, contextual 40-char AWS secret keys, GitHub tokens, OpenAI/Anthropic/Google/Stripe/Slack tokens, JWTs, bearer tokens, authenticated DB/Redis connection strings, PEM private keys, and generic quoted API-key-like assignments (`packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:18`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:26`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:31`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:36`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:41`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:46`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:56`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:61`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:66`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:71`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:76`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:81`).\n\nThe scrubber is sequential and fail-open: it resets each regex `lastIndex`, applies `replace`, records deduplicated pattern IDs in a `Set`, and returns original text with no redactions if anything throws (`packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:90`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:93`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:96`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:100`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:101`). The write path invokes `scrubSecrets(input.content)` immediately in `learn()`, before deduplication, existing-row lookup, insert, markdown export, embedding enqueue, and auto-relation work (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:304`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:307`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:314`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:317`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:352`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:394`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:401`). It logs only count and pattern IDs, not secret values (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:309`). It derives fallback titles from scrubbed content, but caller-provided `title`, `source`, `project_scope`, and `provenanceMetadata` are not scrubbed in the shown path (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:350`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:361`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:382`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:383`).\n\nI found no dedicated scrubber test in the scoped `packages/openltm-core/src/__tests__/*`; the files visible there are CLI/install and extension capability tests (`packages/openltm-core/src/__tests__/cli.test.ts:1`, `packages/openltm-core/src/__tests__/extensions.test.ts:1`). In system-spec-kit, direct `memory_save` parses file content and persists `parsed.content` as `contentText` into `memory_index`, while the existing redaction gate is scoped to extracted working-memory summaries and stores only a redaction flag, not redacted content (`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/parsing/memory-parser.ts:244`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/handlers/save/create-record.ts:316`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/vector-index-mutations.ts:301`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/extraction/extraction-adapter.ts:246`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/cognitive/working-memory.ts:449`).\n\n## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n- **Claim** · Add a pre-index secret scrubber on `memory_save` content before embedding, FTS, BM25, and `content_text` persistence · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:307`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:352`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/handlers/save/create-record.ts:328` · **Maps-to** · `memory_save` ingest pipeline · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.88 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user local storage still leaks secrets into SQLite/vector caches; FSRS/causal/self-maintenance do not mitigate secret persistence.\n- **Claim** · Run redaction before dedup/content-hash decisions so two otherwise identical memories differing only by secret value collapse safely · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:307`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:314`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/handlers/memory-save.ts:2521` · **Maps-to** · `checkContentHashDedup` / `computeContentHash` · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.82 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our lineage and causal edges preserve version history, but hashing raw secrets first can still create secret-derived durable identifiers.\n- **Claim** · Keep typed redaction markers instead of generic `[REDACTED]` for operator diagnosis without exposing values · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:21`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:37`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/extraction/redaction-gate.ts:61` · **Maps-to** · extraction redaction gate and new memory-save scrubber · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our current generic marker is safer but less auditable; typed categories help tune false positives while preserving local privacy.\n- **Claim** · Preserve our high-entropy false-positive exclusions if adopting broader secret patterns · **Evidence** · `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/extraction/redaction-gate.ts:21`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/extraction/redaction-gate.ts:44`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/extraction/redaction-gate.ts:48` · **Maps-to** · new sub-packet · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.84 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · OpenLTM lacks generic high-entropy matching, while our existing exclusions avoid redacting git SHAs and UUIDs.\n- **Claim** · Add targeted tests for every secret class and for benign long tokens · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/__tests__/cli.test.ts:1`, `packages/openltm-core/src/__tests__/extensions.test.ts:1`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/tests/redaction-gate.vitest.ts:9` · **Maps-to** · memory-save security tests · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.78 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · We already test extraction redaction; the missing part is write-path persistence coverage.\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-006.md","text":"# Iteration 006 — Secret redaction before write\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.68 · **tokens:** 107290 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nOpenLTM implements redaction as a fixed ordered `PATTERNS` array of `{id, regex, replacement}` objects, replacing matches with typed placeholders such as `[REDACTED:aws-access-key]` and `[REDACTED:jwt]` (`packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:21`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:62`). The pattern set covers AWS access keys, contextual 40-char AWS secret keys, GitHub tokens, OpenAI/Anthropic/Google/Stripe/Slack tokens, JWTs, bearer tokens, authenticated DB/Redis connection strings, PEM private keys, and generic quoted API-key-like assignments (`packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:18`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:26`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:31`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:36`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:41`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:46`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:56`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:61`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:66`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:71`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:76`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:81`).\n\nThe scrubber is sequential and fail-open: it resets each regex `lastIndex`, applies `replace`, records deduplicated pattern IDs in a `Set`, and returns original text with no redactions if anything throws (`packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:90`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:93`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:96`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:100`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:101`). The write path invokes `scrubSecrets(input.content)` immediately in `learn()`, before deduplication, existing-row lookup, insert, markdown export, embedding enqueue, and auto-relation work (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:304`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:307`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:314`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:317`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:352`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:394`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:401`). It logs only count and pattern IDs, not secret values (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:309`). It derives fallback titles from scrubbed content, but caller-provided `title`, `source`, `project_scope`, and `provenanceMetadata` are not scrubbed in the shown path (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:350`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:361`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:382`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:383`).\n\nI found no dedicated scrubber test in the scoped `packages/openltm-core/src/__tests__/*`; the files visible there are CLI/install and extension capability tests (`packages/openltm-core/src/__tests__/cli.test.ts:1`, `packages/openltm-core/src/__tests__/extensions.test.ts:1`). In system-spec-kit, direct `memory_save` parses file content and persists `parsed.content` as `contentText` into `memory_index`, while the existing redaction gate is scoped to extracted working-memory summaries and stores only a redaction flag, not redacted content (`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/parsing/memory-parser.ts:244`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/handlers/save/create-record.ts:316`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/vector-index-mutations.ts:301`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/extraction/extraction-adapter.ts:246`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/cognitive/working-memory.ts:449`).\n\n## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n- **Claim** · Add a pre-index secret scrubber on `memory_save` content before embedding, FTS, BM25, and `content_text` persistence · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:307`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:352`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/handlers/save/create-record.ts:328` · **Maps-to** · `memory_save` ingest pipeline · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.88 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user local storage still leaks secrets into SQLite/vector caches; FSRS/causal/self-maintenance do not mitigate secret persistence.\n- **Claim** · Run redaction before dedup/content-hash decisions so two otherwise identical memories differing only by secret value collapse safely · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:307`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:314`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/handlers/memory-save.ts:2521` · **Maps-to** · `checkContentHashDedup` / `computeContentHash` · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.82 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our lineage and causal edges preserve version history, but hashing raw secrets first can still create secret-derived durable identifiers.\n- **Claim** · Keep typed redaction markers instead of generic `[REDACTED]` for operator diagnosis without exposing values · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:21`, `packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:37`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/extraction/redaction-gate.ts:61` · **Maps-to** · extraction redaction gate and new memory-save scrubber · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our current generic marker is safer but less auditable; typed categories help tune false positives while preserving local privacy.\n- **Claim** · Preserve our high-entropy false-positive exclusions if adopting broader secret patterns · **Evidence** · `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/extraction/redaction-gate.ts:21`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/extraction/redaction-gate.ts:44`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/extraction/redaction-gate.ts:48` · **Maps-to** · new sub-packet · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.84 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · OpenLTM lacks generic high-entropy matching, while our existing exclusions avoid redacting git SHAs and UUIDs.\n- **Claim** · Add targeted tests for every secret class and for benign long tokens · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/__tests__/cli.test.ts:1`, `packages/openltm-core/src/__tests__/extensions.test.ts:1`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/tests/redaction-gate.vitest.ts:9` · **Maps-to** · memory-save security tests · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.78 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · We already test extraction redaction; the missing part is write-path persistence coverage.\n\n## Negative knowledge\n- Do not copy OpenLTM’s fail-open behavior unchanged; returning original text on scrubber failure can persist the exact secret.\n- Do not scrub only `content`; titles, trigger phrases, provenance metadata, and routing summaries can also carry secrets.\n- Do not copy the broad generic API-key regex without calibration; it can over-redact whole quoted assignment fragments.\n- Do not redact emails by default in long-term spec memory unless a privacy policy requires it; project docs often contain legitimate contact identifiers.\n\n## Open questions\n- Should redacted canonical spec files be rewritten, or should only the indexed `content_text`, embeddings, and FTS rows be scrubbed?\n- Should redaction block the save when the redaction ratio is high, matching our extraction skip-threshold pattern?\n- Should secret-redaction metadata become searchable/auditable as a governance field without storing matched values?\n\nDELTA_JSON: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"run\":1,\"iteration\":\"006\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"status\":\"insight\",\"focus\":\"Secret redaction before write\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.68,\"findingsCount\":5,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADOPT: Add a pre-index secret scrubber on `memory_save` content before embedding, FTS, BM25, and `content_text` persistence\",\"ADAPT: Run redaction before dedup/content-hash decisions so two otherwise identical memories differing only by secret value collapse safely\",\"ADAPT: Keep typed redaction markers instead of generic `[REDACTED]` for operator diagnosis without exposing values\"],\"sources\":[\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:17\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:21\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:62\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:18\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:26\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:31\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:36\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:41\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:46\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:51\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:56\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:61\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:66\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:71\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:76\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:81\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:90\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:93\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:96\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:100\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/secretsScrubber.ts:101\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:304\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:307\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:314\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:317\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:352\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:394\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:401\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:309\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:350\",\"packages/openltm-cor... (line truncated to 2000 chars)","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":32,"totalLines":32,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-006.md","time":{"start":1780926450495,"end":1780926450536}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_036408d1c76c14fc016a26c7f25a2c81918500e2b31e480c56"}},"id":"prt_ea77d0b3d001aQj32491tQpixS","sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","messageID":"msg_ea77cc18a001W0nhx4yXBV8BDy"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780926450557,"sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_69y9AjzLdV4B72aL49ve5p9O","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-005.md","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-005.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 005 — Typed knowledge graph + BFS conflict detection\n2: \n3: **Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.64 · **tokens:** 102963 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n4: \n5: ---\n6: \n7: ## Mechanism\n8: OpenLTM defines exactly six relation types in both TypeScript and SQLite: `supports`, `contradicts`, `refines`, `depends_on`, `related_to`, `supersedes` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:29`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:30`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:95`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:100`). Relations have optional `note` and bounded `weight`, and migration text says effective weight is “base × decay” at read time (`migrations/018_relation_semantics.sql:1`, `migrations/018_relation_semantics.sql:7`). In the inspected traversal path, however, `getNeighbors()` selects only neighbor id and relation type, not weight or note (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:56`). `relate()` validates source/target existence, then `INSERT OR IGNORE`s only source, target, and type, so it creates but does not update edge metadata (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:587`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:603`).\n9: \n10: Graph reasoning is an undirected BFS over `memory_relations`: outgoing and incoming edges are unioned (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:56`), traversal starts from an active seed and stops at `depth` (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:69`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:93`), and visited nodes are queued once (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:111`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:115`). It classifies `contradicts` and `supersedes` as conflicts, and `supports` and `refines` as reinforcements (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:39`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:40`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:105`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:109`). `depends_on` and `related_to` are traversed but not surfaced as conflict/reinforcement buckets.\n11: \n12: Implicit relation inference is bounded: only pairs among the first six visited nodes are considered, capping inference at 15 pairs (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:161`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:164`). If enabled, OpenLTM classifies missing edges and persists them via `relate()` (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:122`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:143`). Separately, `learn()` fire-and-forgets auto-relation detection after embedding, using top-5 similar memories at threshold `0.6` unless `autoRelate` is disabled (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:273`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:284`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:400`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:405`). The classifier can auto-create only `supports`, `contradicts`, `refines`, or `related_to`; `supersedes` and `depends_on` are excluded from auto-inference (`packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:306`, `packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:315`).\n13: \n14: Ordinary `recall()` does FTS5 query expansion, optional semantic fallback at similarity threshold `0.5`, filters to `status = 'active'`, enriches rows with direct relations, and returns them; it does not build the BFS conflict summary in the inspected body (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:417`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:462`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:510`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:562`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:584`). Optional context graphing exists via `getContextMergeWithGraph()`: when `ltm.graphReasoning` is enabled, it seeds BFS from two globals plus one scoped memory at depth 2 and emits up to five reasoning lines (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:682`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:702`). Conflict lines explicitly warn “verify before applying” (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:235`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:239`). The conflict inspection view also treats only `contradicts` and `supersedes` as conflicts (`migrations/004_graph_reasoning.sql:5`, `migrations/004_graph_reasoning.sql:18`). Supersession has schema support via `status='superseded'`, `superseded_by`, and `superseded_at`, but `relate({relationship_type:'supersedes'})` does not itself update those fields (`packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:50`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:58`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:587`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:603`).\n15: \n16: ## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n17: - **Claim** · Surface contradiction/supersession warnings inline with retrieval/context, not only in graph-debug tools · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:235`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:682` · **Maps-to** · `memory_search` / `memory_context` response envelope · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.84 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our causal model already has `contradicts`/`supersedes`; the transferable delta is recall-adjacent presentation, not schema.\n18: - **Claim** · Treat `supersedes` as retrieval suppression/demotion only when coupled to explicit record state · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:50`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:510`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:587` · **Maps-to** · causal-edge write path plus memory-state/archival policy · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · HIGH · **Confidence** · 0.78 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · FSRS decay should not be overridden by a bare edge unless the newer record is verified authoritative.\n19: - **Claim** · Keep implicit relation inference bounded and shadow-first · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:284`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:161`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:164` · **Maps-to** · `memory_causal_stats` backfill / shadow feedback reducers · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · The bounds fit local single-user operation, but auto-writing contradictions risks false conflict pollution.\n20: - **Claim** · Do not add edge `weight` unless traversal/scoring consumes it · **Evidence** · `migrations/018_relation_semantics.sql:2`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:600` · **Maps-to** · causal-edge strength scoring · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.91 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our causal edges already carry strength; copying an unused metadata column would be dead surface area.\n21: - **Claim** · Reuse compact conflict copy, not OpenLTM’s separate graph UI machinery · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:224`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:248`, `src/cluster.ts:8` · **Maps-to** · response formatter; graph UI as new sub-packet only · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.80 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · A five-line “verify before applying” block improves agent behavior without adding UI/layout state.\n22: \n23: ## Negative knowledge\n24: Do not copy `relate()` as-is: `INSERT OR IGNORE` prevents metadata updates and does not enact supersession state.\n25: \n26: Do not copy the full cluster/layout subsystem into retrieval: label propagation and pinned coordinates are graph-UI concerns, not continuity quality (`src/cluster.ts:8`, `migrations/016_memory_layout.sql:2`).\n27: \n28: Do not assume OpenLTM auto-detects supersession: its classifier excludes `supersedes` and `depends_on` (`packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:306`, `packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:317`).\n29: \n30: ## Open questions\n31: Should system-spec-kit make `contradicts`/`supersedes` checks default in `memory_search`, or only when `includeTrace`/debug profile is enabled?\n32: \n33: Should a `supersedes` causal edge automatically change memory state, or require explicit validation evidence first?\n34: \n35: Can shadow feedback estimate false-positive contradiction warnings before enabling inline recall blocking?\n36: \n37: DELTA_JSON: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"run\":1,\"iteration\":\"005\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"status\":\"insight\",\"focus\":\"Typed knowledge graph + BFS conflict detection\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.64,\"findingsCount\":5,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: Surface contradiction/supersession warnings inline with retrieval/context, not only in graph-debug tools\",\"ADAPT: Treat `supersedes` as retrieval suppression/demotion only when coupled to explicit record state\",\"ADAPT: Keep implicit relation inference bounded and shadow-first\"],\"sources\":[\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:29\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:30\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:95\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:100\",\"migrations/018_relation_semantics.sql:1\",\"migrations/018_relation_semantics.sql:7\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:51\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:56\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:587\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:603\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:69\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:93\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:111\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:115\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:39\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:40\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:105\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:109\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:161\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:164\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:122\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:143\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:273\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:284\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:400\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:405\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:306\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:315\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:417\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:462\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:510\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:562\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:584\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:682\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:702\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:235\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:239\",\"migrations/004_gr... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(End of file - total 37 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 005 — Typed knowledge graph + BFS conflict detection\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.64 · **tokens:** 102963 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nOpenLTM defines exactly six relation types in both TypeScript and SQLite: `supports`, `contradicts`, `refines`, `depends_on`, `related_to`, `supersedes` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:29`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:30`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:95`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:100`). Relations have optional `note` and bounded `weight`, and migration text says effective weight is “base × decay” at read time (`migrations/018_relation_semantics.sql:1`, `migrations/018_relation_semantics.sql:7`). In the inspected traversal path, however, `getNeighbors()` selects only neighbor id and relation type, not weight or note (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:56`). `relate()` validates source/target existence, then `INSERT OR IGNORE`s only source, target, and type, so it creates but does not update edge metadata (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:587`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:603`).\n\nGraph reasoning is an undirected BFS over `memory_relations`: outgoing and incoming edges are unioned (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:56`), traversal starts from an active seed and stops at `depth` (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:69`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:93`), and visited nodes are queued once (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:111`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:115`). It classifies `contradicts` and `supersedes` as conflicts, and `supports` and `refines` as reinforcements (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:39`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:40`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:105`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:109`). `depends_on` and `related_to` are traversed but not surfaced as conflict/reinforcement buckets.\n\nImplicit relation inference is bounded: only pairs among the first six visited nodes are considered, capping inference at 15 pairs (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:161`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:164`). If enabled, OpenLTM classifies missing edges and persists them via `relate()` (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:122`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:143`). Separately, `learn()` fire-and-forgets auto-relation detection after embedding, using top-5 similar memories at threshold `0.6` unless `autoRelate` is disabled (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:273`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:284`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:400`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:405`). The classifier can auto-create only `supports`, `contradicts`, `refines`, or `related_to`; `supersedes` and `depends_on` are excluded from auto-inference (`packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:306`, `packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:315`).\n\nOrdinary `recall()` does FTS5 query expansion, optional semantic fallback at similarity threshold `0.5`, filters to `status = 'active'`, enriches rows with direct relations, and returns them; it does not build the BFS conflict summary in the inspected body (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:417`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:462`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:510`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:562`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:584`). Optional context graphing exists via `getContextMergeWithGraph()`: when `ltm.graphReasoning` is enabled, it seeds BFS from two globals plus one scoped memory at depth 2 and emits up to five reasoning lines (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:682`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:702`). Conflict lines explicitly warn “verify before applying” (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:235`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:239`). The conflict inspection view also treats only `contradicts` and `supersedes` as conflicts (`migrations/004_graph_reasoning.sql:5`, `migrations/004_graph_reasoning.sql:18`). Supersession has schema support via `status='superseded'`, `superseded_by`, and `superseded_at`, but `relate({relationship_type:'supersedes'})` does not itself update those fields (`packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:50`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:58`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:587`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:603`).\n\n## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n- **Claim** · Surface contradiction/supersession warnings inline with retrieval/context, not only in graph-debug tools · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:235`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:682` · **Maps-to** · `memory_search` / `memory_context` response envelope · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.84 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our causal model already has `contradicts`/`supersedes`; the transferable delta is recall-adjacent presentation, not schema.\n- **Claim** · Treat `supersedes` as retrieval suppression/demotion only when coupled to explicit record state · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:50`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:510`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:587` · **Maps-to** · causal-edge write path plus memory-state/archival policy · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · HIGH · **Confidence** · 0.78 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · FSRS decay should not be overridden by a bare edge unless the newer record is verified authoritative.\n- **Claim** · Keep implicit relation inference bounded and shadow-first · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:284`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:161`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:164` · **Maps-to** · `memory_causal_stats` backfill / shadow feedback reducers · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · The bounds fit local single-user operation, but auto-writing contradictions risks false conflict pollution.\n- **Claim** · Do not add edge `weight` unless traversal/scoring consumes it · **Evidence** · `migrations/018_relation_semantics.sql:2`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:600` · **Maps-to** · causal-edge strength scoring · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.91 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our causal edges already carry strength; copying an unused metadata column would be dead surface area.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-005.md","text":"# Iteration 005 — Typed knowledge graph + BFS conflict detection\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.64 · **tokens:** 102963 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nOpenLTM defines exactly six relation types in both TypeScript and SQLite: `supports`, `contradicts`, `refines`, `depends_on`, `related_to`, `supersedes` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:29`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:30`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:95`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:100`). Relations have optional `note` and bounded `weight`, and migration text says effective weight is “base × decay” at read time (`migrations/018_relation_semantics.sql:1`, `migrations/018_relation_semantics.sql:7`). In the inspected traversal path, however, `getNeighbors()` selects only neighbor id and relation type, not weight or note (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:56`). `relate()` validates source/target existence, then `INSERT OR IGNORE`s only source, target, and type, so it creates but does not update edge metadata (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:587`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:603`).\n\nGraph reasoning is an undirected BFS over `memory_relations`: outgoing and incoming edges are unioned (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:56`), traversal starts from an active seed and stops at `depth` (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:69`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:93`), and visited nodes are queued once (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:111`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:115`). It classifies `contradicts` and `supersedes` as conflicts, and `supports` and `refines` as reinforcements (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:39`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:40`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:105`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:109`). `depends_on` and `related_to` are traversed but not surfaced as conflict/reinforcement buckets.\n\nImplicit relation inference is bounded: only pairs among the first six visited nodes are considered, capping inference at 15 pairs (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:161`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:164`). If enabled, OpenLTM classifies missing edges and persists them via `relate()` (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:122`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:143`). Separately, `learn()` fire-and-forgets auto-relation detection after embedding, using top-5 similar memories at threshold `0.6` unless `autoRelate` is disabled (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:273`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:284`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:400`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:405`). The classifier can auto-create only `supports`, `contradicts`, `refines`, or `related_to`; `supersedes` and `depends_on` are excluded from auto-inference (`packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:306`, `packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:315`).\n\nOrdinary `recall()` does FTS5 query expansion, optional semantic fallback at similarity threshold `0.5`, filters to `status = 'active'`, enriches rows with direct relations, and returns them; it does not build the BFS conflict summary in the inspected body (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:417`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:462`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:510`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:562`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:584`). Optional context graphing exists via `getContextMergeWithGraph()`: when `ltm.graphReasoning` is enabled, it seeds BFS from two globals plus one scoped memory at depth 2 and emits up to five reasoning lines (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:682`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:702`). Conflict lines explicitly warn “verify before applying” (`packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:235`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:239`). The conflict inspection view also treats only `contradicts` and `supersedes` as conflicts (`migrations/004_graph_reasoning.sql:5`, `migrations/004_graph_reasoning.sql:18`). Supersession has schema support via `status='superseded'`, `superseded_by`, and `superseded_at`, but `relate({relationship_type:'supersedes'})` does not itself update those fields (`packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:50`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:58`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:587`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:603`).\n\n## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n- **Claim** · Surface contradiction/supersession warnings inline with retrieval/context, not only in graph-debug tools · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:235`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:682` · **Maps-to** · `memory_search` / `memory_context` response envelope · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.84 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our causal model already has `contradicts`/`supersedes`; the transferable delta is recall-adjacent presentation, not schema.\n- **Claim** · Treat `supersedes` as retrieval suppression/demotion only when coupled to explicit record state · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:50`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:510`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:587` · **Maps-to** · causal-edge write path plus memory-state/archival policy · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · HIGH · **Confidence** · 0.78 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · FSRS decay should not be overridden by a bare edge unless the newer record is verified authoritative.\n- **Claim** · Keep implicit relation inference bounded and shadow-first · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:284`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:161`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:164` · **Maps-to** · `memory_causal_stats` backfill / shadow feedback reducers · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · The bounds fit local single-user operation, but auto-writing contradictions risks false conflict pollution.\n- **Claim** · Do not add edge `weight` unless traversal/scoring consumes it · **Evidence** · `migrations/018_relation_semantics.sql:2`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:600` · **Maps-to** · causal-edge strength scoring · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.91 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our causal edges already carry strength; copying an unused metadata column would be dead surface area.\n- **Claim** · Reuse compact conflict copy, not OpenLTM’s separate graph UI machinery · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:224`, `packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:248`, `src/cluster.ts:8` · **Maps-to** · response formatter; graph UI as new sub-packet only · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.80 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · A five-line “verify before applying” block improves agent behavior without adding UI/layout state.\n\n## Negative knowledge\nDo not copy `relate()` as-is: `INSERT OR IGNORE` prevents metadata updates and does not enact supersession state.\n\nDo not copy the full cluster/layout subsystem into retrieval: label propagation and pinned coordinates are graph-UI concerns, not continuity quality (`src/cluster.ts:8`, `migrations/016_memory_layout.sql:2`).\n\nDo not assume OpenLTM auto-detects supersession: its classifier excludes `supersedes` and `depends_on` (`packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:306`, `packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:317`).\n\n## Open questions\nShould system-spec-kit make `contradicts`/`supersedes` checks default in `memory_search`, or only when `includeTrace`/debug profile is enabled?\n\nShould a `supersedes` causal edge automatically change memory state, or require explicit validation evidence first?\n\nCan shadow feedback estimate false-positive contradiction warnings before enabling inline recall blocking?\n\nDELTA_JSON: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"run\":1,\"iteration\":\"005\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"status\":\"insight\",\"focus\":\"Typed knowledge graph + BFS conflict detection\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.64,\"findingsCount\":5,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: Surface contradiction/supersession warnings inline with retrieval/context, not only in graph-debug tools\",\"ADAPT: Treat `supersedes` as retrieval suppression/demotion only when coupled to explicit record state\",\"ADAPT: Keep implicit relation inference bounded and shadow-first\"],\"sources\":[\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:29\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:30\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:95\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:100\",\"migrations/018_relation_semantics.sql:1\",\"migrations/018_relation_semantics.sql:7\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:51\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:56\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:587\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:603\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:69\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:93\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:111\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:115\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:39\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:40\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:105\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:109\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:161\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:164\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:122\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:143\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:273\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:284\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:400\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:405\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:306\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/embeddings.ts:315\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:417\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:462\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:510\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:562\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:584\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:682\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:702\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:235\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/graph.ts:239\",\"migrations/004_gr... (line truncated to 2000 chars)","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":37,"totalLines":37,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-005.md","time":{"start":1780926450492,"end":1780926450538}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_036408d1c76c14fc016a26c7f25a208191a188a63b9c1bb570"}},"id":"prt_ea77d0b3a001WRg5W2v4xHb8nB","sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","messageID":"msg_ea77cc18a001W0nhx4yXBV8BDy"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780926450557,"sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_pfpJ5Ee4ZgmCFH9K1lbKHLV8","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-003.md","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-003.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 003 — Janitor background-maintenance pipeline (promotion + dedup staging)\n2: \n3: **Status:** insight · **Findings:** 6 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.72 · **tokens:** 102477 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n4: \n5: ---\n6: \n7: ## Mechanism\n8: OpenLTM’s janitor is an explicit sequential pass guarded against concurrent runs, with per-stage error capture and run-result counters (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:52`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:74`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:116`). The order is embed missing memories, decay, archive, promote, then dedup-stage (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:75`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:82`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:89`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:96`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:103`). It persists last-run counters in `settings`, seeded by migration 012, then runs WAL checkpoint and `ANALYZE` hygiene (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:130`, `migrations/012_seed_janitor_settings.sql:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:139`).\n9: \n10: Scheduling is optional: `ltm.janitor.intervalMinutes` defaults to `0`, so auto-run is disabled unless configured (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/providers/types.ts:140`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:183`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:189`). A separate Honker scheduler defines `@every 6h`, leader-elected enqueue, worker claim/retry, and inert fallback when Honker is unavailable; actual server startup wiring is UNKNOWN from the scoped files (`packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:18`, `packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:10`, `packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:61`, `packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:75`).\n11: \n12: Embedding maintenance uses a `memory_embeddings` side table with model/dim metadata and optional vec0 dual-write (`migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:36`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:48`). The janitor asks for up to 10,000 missing IDs and embeds batches of 50 by default (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:86`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:92`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:107`). Caveat: the missing-ID DAO filters only `status='active'`, while the later fetch allows active/pending, so pending proposal embedding is effectively UNKNOWN/active-only (`packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:69`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:99`).\n13: \n14: Decay is materialized: migration 011 adds indexed `decay_score`, and recall uses `ORDER BY decay_score DESC` for default relevance (`migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:4`, `migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:6`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:524`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:526`). The formula is `importance * confidence * 0.5^(age/half_life)`, except importance 5 and `confirm_count >= 10` do not age-decay; half-lives are 180/90/30/14 days for importance 4/3/2/else (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:14`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:20`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:22`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:24`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:26`). Deprecation triggers at `importance < 5`, `confirm_count < 10`, and `decay_score < 0.25`; archive later evicts only deprecated, importance <=2, recall_count <=1, score <0.10, max 100/run, preserving JSON first (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:31`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:4`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:49`).\n15: \n16: Promotion scans active unlinked `context_items` of type decision/gotcha with content >20 chars, dedups by normalized key, then creates `status='pending'` memories with source `auto-promote`, confidence 0.8, architecture/gotcha category, gotcha importance 4, and decision importance default 3 (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:64`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:83`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:89`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/providers/types.ts:139`). Approval flips pending to active; rejection deletes the pending memory and resets the context item (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:112`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:122`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:134`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:146`). Dedup intends pairwise active-memory cosine matching at 0.85 plus optional LLM JSON verdict, then saves pending `dedup:idA:idB` proposals; however it still selects `memories.embedding` even though migration 010 drops that column, so the current dedup pass appears schema-stale (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:73`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:90`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:114`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:160`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:211`, `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:24`).\n17: \n18: ## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n19: - **Claim** · Add a low-frequency maintenance report, not a replacement for the self-maintaining index · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:130`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:139` · **Maps-to** · `memory_health`, `memory_index_scan`, `memory_embedding_reconcile` · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.88 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our incremental index is better for freshness, but explicit last-run counters and hygiene summaries improve operator trust.\n20: - **Claim** · Introduce a pending promotion tier for mined continuity insights before durable memory admission · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:89` · **Maps-to** · shadow feedback reducers or new sub-packet · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user does not remove quality risk; review-before-activation fits our spec ladder and FSRS can score after approval.\n21: - **Claim** · Stage semantic dedup as proposals, never auto-merge memory records · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:103`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:211` · **Maps-to** · new dedup proposal queue plus causal-edge preservation · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.90 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our causal edges make destructive merge riskier; staged review preserves lineage.\n22: - **Claim** · Do not copy OpenLTM’s decay formula; adapt only stale-candidate reporting · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:4` · **Maps-to** · FSRS decay, retention sweep · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.82 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · FSRS/co-activation is richer than fixed half-lives, but archive-style candidates could aid audits.\n23: - **Claim** · Treat embedding/dedup schema drift as a warning for separate vector stores · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:90`, `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:24` · **Maps-to** · `memory_embedding_reconcile` tests · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.84 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our separate vector store has the same drift class, so reconciliation tests matter more than janitor cleverness.\n24: - **Claim** · Defer leader-elected cron complexity · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:53`, `packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:61` · **Maps-to** · daemon scheduling/new sub-packet · **Verdict** · DEFER · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.79 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Local single-user system-spec-kit usually needs coalesced maintenance, not distributed cron ownership.\n25: \n26: ## Negative knowledge\n27: Do not copy fixed half-life decay as the primary relevance model; FSRS plus co-activation is more expressive. Do not copy O(n²) all-pairs dedup as-is; use vector top-K/proposal staging. Do not hard-archive spec continuity by simple score thresholds; governed retention and provenance should dominate. Do not adopt Honker-style scheduling unless we first prove current self-maintenance leaves stale work.\n28: \n29: ## Open questions\n30: Should system-spec-kit expose a first-class `pending_memory_proposals` review surface? Should dedup proposals preserve causal edges as `supports`/`supersedes` candidates instead of merges? Should maintenance reporting be a dry-run janitor dashboard over existing tools rather than a new writer?\n31: \n32: DELTA_JSON: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"run\":1,\"iteration\":\"003\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"status\":\"insight\",\"focus\":\"Janitor background-maintenance pipeline (promotion + dedup staging)\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.72,\"findingsCount\":6,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: Add a low-frequency maintenance report, not a replacement for the self-maintaining index\",\"ADOPT: Introduce a pending promotion tier for mined continuity insights before durable memory admission\",\"ADOPT: Stage semantic dedup as proposals, never auto-merge memory records\"],\"sources\":[\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:51\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:52\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:74\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:116\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:75\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:82\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:89\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:96\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:103\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:130\",\"migrations/012_seed_janitor_settings.sql:5\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:139\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/providers/types.ts:140\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:183\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:189\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:18\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:10\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:61\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:75\",\"migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:5\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:36\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:48\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:86\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:92\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:107\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:69\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:99\",\"migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:4\",\"migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:6\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:524\",\"... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(End of file - total 32 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 003 — Janitor background-maintenance pipeline (promotion + dedup staging)\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 6 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.72 · **tokens:** 102477 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nOpenLTM’s janitor is an explicit sequential pass guarded against concurrent runs, with per-stage error capture and run-result counters (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:52`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:74`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:116`). The order is embed missing memories, decay, archive, promote, then dedup-stage (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:75`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:82`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:89`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:96`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:103`). It persists last-run counters in `settings`, seeded by migration 012, then runs WAL checkpoint and `ANALYZE` hygiene (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:130`, `migrations/012_seed_janitor_settings.sql:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:139`).\n\nScheduling is optional: `ltm.janitor.intervalMinutes` defaults to `0`, so auto-run is disabled unless configured (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/providers/types.ts:140`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:183`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:189`). A separate Honker scheduler defines `@every 6h`, leader-elected enqueue, worker claim/retry, and inert fallback when Honker is unavailable; actual server startup wiring is UNKNOWN from the scoped files (`packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:18`, `packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:10`, `packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:61`, `packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:75`).\n\nEmbedding maintenance uses a `memory_embeddings` side table with model/dim metadata and optional vec0 dual-write (`migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:36`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:48`). The janitor asks for up to 10,000 missing IDs and embeds batches of 50 by default (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:86`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:92`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:107`). Caveat: the missing-ID DAO filters only `status='active'`, while the later fetch allows active/pending, so pending proposal embedding is effectively UNKNOWN/active-only (`packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:69`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:99`).\n\nDecay is materialized: migration 011 adds indexed `decay_score`, and recall uses `ORDER BY decay_score DESC` for default relevance (`migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:4`, `migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:6`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:524`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:526`). The formula is `importance * confidence * 0.5^(age/half_life)`, except importance 5 and `confirm_count >= 10` do not age-decay; half-lives are 180/90/30/14 days for importance 4/3/2/else (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:14`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:20`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:22`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:24`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:26`). Deprecation triggers at `importance < 5`, `confirm_count < 10`, and `decay_score < 0.25`; archive later evicts only deprecated, importance <=2, recall_count <=1, score <0.10, max 100/run, preserving JSON first (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:31`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:4`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:49`).\n\nPromotion scans active unlinked `context_items` of type decision/gotcha with content >20 chars, dedups by normalized key, then creates `status='pending'` memories with source `auto-promote`, confidence 0.8, architecture/gotcha category, gotcha importance 4, and decision importance default 3 (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:64`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:83`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:89`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/providers/types.ts:139`). Approval flips pending to active; rejection deletes the pending memory and resets the context item (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:112`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:122`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:134`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:146`). Dedup intends pairwise active-memory cosine matching at 0.85 plus optional LLM JSON verdict, then saves pending `dedup:idA:idB` proposals; however it still selects `memories.embedding` even though migration 010 drops that column, so the current dedup pass appears schema-stale (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:73`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:90`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:114`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:160`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:211`, `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:24`).\n\n## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n- **Claim** · Add a low-frequency maintenance report, not a replacement for the self-maintaining index · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:130`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:139` · **Maps-to** · `memory_health`, `memory_index_scan`, `memory_embedding_reconcile` · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.88 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our incremental index is better for freshness, but explicit last-run counters and hygiene summaries improve operator trust.\n- **Claim** · Introduce a pending promotion tier for mined continuity insights before durable memory admission · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:89` · **Maps-to** · shadow feedback reducers or new sub-packet · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user does not remove quality risk; review-before-activation fits our spec ladder and FSRS can score after approval.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-003.md","text":"# Iteration 003 — Janitor background-maintenance pipeline (promotion + dedup staging)\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 6 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.72 · **tokens:** 102477 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nOpenLTM’s janitor is an explicit sequential pass guarded against concurrent runs, with per-stage error capture and run-result counters (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:52`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:74`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:116`). The order is embed missing memories, decay, archive, promote, then dedup-stage (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:75`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:82`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:89`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:96`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:103`). It persists last-run counters in `settings`, seeded by migration 012, then runs WAL checkpoint and `ANALYZE` hygiene (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:130`, `migrations/012_seed_janitor_settings.sql:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:139`).\n\nScheduling is optional: `ltm.janitor.intervalMinutes` defaults to `0`, so auto-run is disabled unless configured (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/providers/types.ts:140`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:183`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:189`). A separate Honker scheduler defines `@every 6h`, leader-elected enqueue, worker claim/retry, and inert fallback when Honker is unavailable; actual server startup wiring is UNKNOWN from the scoped files (`packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:18`, `packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:10`, `packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:61`, `packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:75`).\n\nEmbedding maintenance uses a `memory_embeddings` side table with model/dim metadata and optional vec0 dual-write (`migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:36`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:48`). The janitor asks for up to 10,000 missing IDs and embeds batches of 50 by default (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:86`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:92`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:107`). Caveat: the missing-ID DAO filters only `status='active'`, while the later fetch allows active/pending, so pending proposal embedding is effectively UNKNOWN/active-only (`packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:69`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:99`).\n\nDecay is materialized: migration 011 adds indexed `decay_score`, and recall uses `ORDER BY decay_score DESC` for default relevance (`migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:4`, `migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:6`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:524`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:526`). The formula is `importance * confidence * 0.5^(age/half_life)`, except importance 5 and `confirm_count >= 10` do not age-decay; half-lives are 180/90/30/14 days for importance 4/3/2/else (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:14`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:20`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:22`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:24`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:26`). Deprecation triggers at `importance < 5`, `confirm_count < 10`, and `decay_score < 0.25`; archive later evicts only deprecated, importance <=2, recall_count <=1, score <0.10, max 100/run, preserving JSON first (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:31`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:4`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:49`).\n\nPromotion scans active unlinked `context_items` of type decision/gotcha with content >20 chars, dedups by normalized key, then creates `status='pending'` memories with source `auto-promote`, confidence 0.8, architecture/gotcha category, gotcha importance 4, and decision importance default 3 (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:64`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:83`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:89`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/providers/types.ts:139`). Approval flips pending to active; rejection deletes the pending memory and resets the context item (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:112`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:122`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:134`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:146`). Dedup intends pairwise active-memory cosine matching at 0.85 plus optional LLM JSON verdict, then saves pending `dedup:idA:idB` proposals; however it still selects `memories.embedding` even though migration 010 drops that column, so the current dedup pass appears schema-stale (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:73`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:90`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:114`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:160`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:211`, `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:24`).\n\n## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n- **Claim** · Add a low-frequency maintenance report, not a replacement for the self-maintaining index · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:130`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:139` · **Maps-to** · `memory_health`, `memory_index_scan`, `memory_embedding_reconcile` · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.88 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our incremental index is better for freshness, but explicit last-run counters and hygiene summaries improve operator trust.\n- **Claim** · Introduce a pending promotion tier for mined continuity insights before durable memory admission · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:51`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/promote.ts:89` · **Maps-to** · shadow feedback reducers or new sub-packet · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user does not remove quality risk; review-before-activation fits our spec ladder and FSRS can score after approval.\n- **Claim** · Stage semantic dedup as proposals, never auto-merge memory records · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:103`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:211` · **Maps-to** · new dedup proposal queue plus causal-edge preservation · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.90 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our causal edges make destructive merge riskier; staged review preserves lineage.\n- **Claim** · Do not copy OpenLTM’s decay formula; adapt only stale-candidate reporting · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/decay.ts:17`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/archive.ts:4` · **Maps-to** · FSRS decay, retention sweep · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.82 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · FSRS/co-activation is richer than fixed half-lives, but archive-style candidates could aid audits.\n- **Claim** · Treat embedding/dedup schema drift as a warning for separate vector stores · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:90`, `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:24` · **Maps-to** · `memory_embedding_reconcile` tests · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.84 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our separate vector store has the same drift class, so reconciliation tests matter more than janitor cleverness.\n- **Claim** · Defer leader-elected cron complexity · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:53`, `packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:61` · **Maps-to** · daemon scheduling/new sub-packet · **Verdict** · DEFER · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.79 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Local single-user system-spec-kit usually needs coalesced maintenance, not distributed cron ownership.\n\n## Negative knowledge\nDo not copy fixed half-life decay as the primary relevance model; FSRS plus co-activation is more expressive. Do not copy O(n²) all-pairs dedup as-is; use vector top-K/proposal staging. Do not hard-archive spec continuity by simple score thresholds; governed retention and provenance should dominate. Do not adopt Honker-style scheduling unless we first prove current self-maintenance leaves stale work.\n\n## Open questions\nShould system-spec-kit expose a first-class `pending_memory_proposals` review surface? Should dedup proposals preserve causal edges as `supports`/`supersedes` candidates instead of merges? Should maintenance reporting be a dry-run janitor dashboard over existing tools rather than a new writer?\n\nDELTA_JSON: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"run\":1,\"iteration\":\"003\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"status\":\"insight\",\"focus\":\"Janitor background-maintenance pipeline (promotion + dedup staging)\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.72,\"findingsCount\":6,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: Add a low-frequency maintenance report, not a replacement for the self-maintaining index\",\"ADOPT: Introduce a pending promotion tier for mined continuity insights before durable memory admission\",\"ADOPT: Stage semantic dedup as proposals, never auto-merge memory records\"],\"sources\":[\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:51\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:52\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:74\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:116\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:75\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:82\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:89\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:96\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:103\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:130\",\"migrations/012_seed_janitor_settings.sql:5\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:139\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/providers/types.ts:140\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:183\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/index.ts:189\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:18\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:10\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:61\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/scheduler/index.ts:75\",\"migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:5\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:36\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:48\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:86\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:92\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:107\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dao/embeddings.ts:69\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/embeddings.ts:99\",\"migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:4\",\"migrations/011_add_decay_score_and_archive.sql:6\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:524\",\"... (line truncated to 2000 chars)","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":32,"totalLines":32,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-003.md","time":{"start":1780926450485,"end":1780926450542}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_036408d1c76c14fc016a26c7f25a088191b762bfdd32e40650"}},"id":"prt_ea77d0b2c0016C9D7AVAMyKt92","sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","messageID":"msg_ea77cc18a001W0nhx4yXBV8BDy"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780926450557,"sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_iCtfGz5c9S1EnzJFoY4Ex27H","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-009.md","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-009.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 009 — Schema/DB design + migration discipline\n2: \n3: **Status:** insight · **Findings:** 6 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.55 · **tokens:** 142818 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n4: \n5: ---\n6: \n7: ## Mechanism\n8: OpenLTM uses an idempotent root DDL plus numbered SQL migrations. The root schema defines `schema_migrations(version, applied_at, checksum)` in `schema.sql`, but the actual runner tracks applied files in `_schema_version(version, name, applied_at, checksum)`, so the naming contract is internally inconsistent. Evidence: `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:7`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:11`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:25`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:27`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:32`.\n9: \n10: FTS5 is external-content and trigger-maintained, not a batch-only index. `memories_fts` maps `rowid` to `memories.id` and indexes `title, content`; insert/delete/update triggers synchronously mirror base-table writes using FTS5 delete rows. Evidence: `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:127`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:129`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:132`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:137`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:142`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:147`. `context_items_fts` repeats the same pattern for project context. Evidence: `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:155`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:157`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:164`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:169`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:174`.\n11: \n12: Migration `020_fts_coverage.sql` is the clearest FTS discipline: it drops/recreates `memories_fts`, repopulates from `memories`, then recreates triggers; it also creates/repopulates `context_items_fts` and adds its triggers. Evidence: `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:7`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:9`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:17`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:20`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:24`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:34`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:43`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:50`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:53`.\n13: \n14: The migration runner discovers `*.sql`, requires `NNN_name.sql`, sorts by filename, computes SHA-256, strips comments, splits optional `-- DOWN`, and applies pending migrations in transactions before inserting `_schema_version`. Evidence: `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:44`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:47`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:53`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:72`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:202`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:239`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:242`. `001_baseline.sql` is a no-DDL sentinel that records the baseline created by `schema.sql`. Evidence: `migrations/001_baseline.sql:1`, `migrations/001_baseline.sql:4`, `migrations/001_baseline.sql:7`.\n15: \n16: Connection setup is WAL-first with FK enforcement and busy timeout; `shared-db.ts` executes `schema.sql`, then runs pending migrations, then backfills vec indexes if sqlite-vec exists. Evidence: `packages/openltm-core/src/shared-db.ts:31`, `packages/openltm-core/src/shared-db.ts:36`, `packages/openltm-core/src/shared-db.ts:37`, `packages/openltm-core/src/shared-db.ts:39`, `packages/openltm-core/src/shared-db.ts:42`, `packages/openltm-core/src/shared-db.ts:45`.\n17: \n18: ## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n19: - **Claim** · Move from a single inline integer migration ladder toward checked-in numbered migration files with checksums. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:44`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:72`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/vector-index-schema.ts:1557` · **Maps-to** · `mcp_server/lib/search/vector-index-schema.ts` · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.90 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our v30 inline transaction/compatibility checks are strong, but per-file history and checksum auditability would make schema drift easier to diagnose.\n20: - **Claim** · Use a baseline sentinel when converting legacy inline migrations into file-backed history. · **Evidence** · `migrations/001_baseline.sql:1`, `migrations/001_baseline.sql:8` · **Maps-to** · new sub-packet · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · This fits our existing `schema_version` history without replaying old FSRS/causal/lineage migrations.\n21: - **Claim** · Treat FTS rebuilds as explicit migrations that repopulate from the source table and recreate triggers. · **Evidence** · `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:7`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:17`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:24`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/vector-index-schema.ts:856` · **Maps-to** · `memory_fts` migration discipline · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.82 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · We already have trigger-kept FTS, but OpenLTM’s numbered FTS rebuild pattern is cleaner than burying rebuilds inside inline TypeScript migrations.\n22: - **Claim** · Do not copy OpenLTM’s embedding split as-is because our vectors are already separate profile-sharded SQLite files. · **Evidence** · `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:5`, `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:25`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/constitutional/memory-db-file-topology.md:22`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/constitutional/memory-db-file-topology.md:31` · **Maps-to** · vector store topology · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.95 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our separate canonical DB plus active vector shard supersedes OpenLTM’s same-file side table.\n23: - **Claim** · Add pair-aware migration backups/checkpoints, not OpenLTM’s single-file backup. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:76`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:231`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/constitutional/memory-db-file-topology.md:46` · **Maps-to** · checkpoint/migration safety · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.78 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Pre-migration backups transfer, but system-spec-kit must snapshot index and active vector shard together.\n24: - **Claim** · Publish an authoritative DB spec only if it is kept mechanically aligned with the runner. · **Evidence** · `docs/internal/DB-SPEC.md:496`, `docs/internal/DB-SPEC.md:521`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:25` · **Maps-to** · new sub-packet · **Verdict** · DEFER · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.84 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · OpenLTM’s DB-SPEC is useful, but its `schema_migrations` vs `_schema_version` drift shows docs alone are not enough.\n25: \n26: ## Negative knowledge\n27: Do not copy the split `schema_migrations`/`_schema_version` naming; it creates source-of-truth ambiguity.\n28: \n29: Do not trust same-file rollback unless `DOWN` SQL is executable; `parseMigration()` strips comments, while migrations like `002` have commented-only downs.\n30: \n31: Do not copy single-file DB assumptions; system-spec-kit’s index and vector shard must be backed up, checked, and restored as one unit.\n32: \n33: Do not replace FSRS/causal-edge schema with OpenLTM’s simpler decay/relation model; our current cognitive and causal surfaces are richer.\n34: \n35: ## Open questions\n36: Should system-spec-kit’s inline v30 migration ladder be frozen behind a `001_baseline` and future changes moved to SQL files?\n37: \n38: Should `memory_health` add an explicit FTS5 `integrity-check`/rebuild report for `memory_fts`?\n39: \n40: Should migration checksums be stored per migration while preserving our existing single `schema_version` compatibility gate?\n41: \n42: DELTA_JSON: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"run\":1,\"iteration\":\"009\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"status\":\"insight\",\"focus\":\"Schema/DB design + migration discipline\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.55,\"findingsCount\":6,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: Move from a single inline integer migration ladder toward checked-in numbered migration files with checksums.\",\"ADOPT: Use a baseline sentinel when converting legacy inline migrations into file-backed history.\",\"ADAPT: Treat FTS rebuilds as explicit migrations that repopulate from the source table and recreate triggers.\"],\"sources\":[\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:5\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:7\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:11\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:25\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:27\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:32\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:127\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:129\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:132\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:137\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:142\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:147\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:155\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:157\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:164\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:169\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:174\",\"migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:7\",\"migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:9\",\"migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:17\",\"migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:20\",\"migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:24\",\"migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:34\",\"migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:43\",\"migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:50\",\"migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:53\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:44\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:47\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:53\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:72\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:202\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:239\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:242\",\"migrations/001_baseline.sql:1\",\"migrations/001_baseline.sql:4\",\"migrations/00... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(End of file - total 42 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 009 — Schema/DB design + migration discipline\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 6 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.55 · **tokens:** 142818 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nOpenLTM uses an idempotent root DDL plus numbered SQL migrations. The root schema defines `schema_migrations(version, applied_at, checksum)` in `schema.sql`, but the actual runner tracks applied files in `_schema_version(version, name, applied_at, checksum)`, so the naming contract is internally inconsistent. Evidence: `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:7`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:11`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:25`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:27`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:32`.\n\nFTS5 is external-content and trigger-maintained, not a batch-only index. `memories_fts` maps `rowid` to `memories.id` and indexes `title, content`; insert/delete/update triggers synchronously mirror base-table writes using FTS5 delete rows. Evidence: `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:127`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:129`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:132`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:137`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:142`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:147`. `context_items_fts` repeats the same pattern for project context. Evidence: `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:155`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:157`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:164`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:169`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:174`.\n\nMigration `020_fts_coverage.sql` is the clearest FTS discipline: it drops/recreates `memories_fts`, repopulates from `memories`, then recreates triggers; it also creates/repopulates `context_items_fts` and adds its triggers. Evidence: `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:7`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:9`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:17`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:20`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:24`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:34`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:43`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:50`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:53`.\n\nThe migration runner discovers `*.sql`, requires `NNN_name.sql`, sorts by filename, computes SHA-256, strips comments, splits optional `-- DOWN`, and applies pending migrations in transactions before inserting `_schema_version`. Evidence: `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:44`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:47`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:53`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:72`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:202`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:239`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:242`. `001_baseline.sql` is a no-DDL sentinel that records the baseline created by `schema.sql`. Evidence: `migrations/001_baseline.sql:1`, `migrations/001_baseline.sql:4`, `migrations/001_baseline.sql:7`.\n\nConnection setup is WAL-first with FK enforcement and busy timeout; `shared-db.ts` executes `schema.sql`, then runs pending migrations, then backfills vec indexes if sqlite-vec exists. Evidence: `packages/openltm-core/src/shared-db.ts:31`, `packages/openltm-core/src/shared-db.ts:36`, `packages/openltm-core/src/shared-db.ts:37`, `packages/openltm-core/src/shared-db.ts:39`, `packages/openltm-core/src/shared-db.ts:42`, `packages/openltm-core/src/shared-db.ts:45`.\n\n## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n- **Claim** · Move from a single inline integer migration ladder toward checked-in numbered migration files with checksums. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:44`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:72`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/vector-index-schema.ts:1557` · **Maps-to** · `mcp_server/lib/search/vector-index-schema.ts` · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.90 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our v30 inline transaction/compatibility checks are strong, but per-file history and checksum auditability would make schema drift easier to diagnose.\n- **Claim** · Use a baseline sentinel when converting legacy inline migrations into file-backed history. · **Evidence** · `migrations/001_baseline.sql:1`, `migrations/001_baseline.sql:8` · **Maps-to** · new sub-packet · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · This fits our existing `schema_version` history without replaying old FSRS/causal/lineage migrations.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-009.md","text":"# Iteration 009 — Schema/DB design + migration discipline\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 6 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.55 · **tokens:** 142818 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nOpenLTM uses an idempotent root DDL plus numbered SQL migrations. The root schema defines `schema_migrations(version, applied_at, checksum)` in `schema.sql`, but the actual runner tracks applied files in `_schema_version(version, name, applied_at, checksum)`, so the naming contract is internally inconsistent. Evidence: `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:7`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:11`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:25`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:27`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:32`.\n\nFTS5 is external-content and trigger-maintained, not a batch-only index. `memories_fts` maps `rowid` to `memories.id` and indexes `title, content`; insert/delete/update triggers synchronously mirror base-table writes using FTS5 delete rows. Evidence: `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:127`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:129`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:132`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:137`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:142`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:147`. `context_items_fts` repeats the same pattern for project context. Evidence: `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:155`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:157`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:164`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:169`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:174`.\n\nMigration `020_fts_coverage.sql` is the clearest FTS discipline: it drops/recreates `memories_fts`, repopulates from `memories`, then recreates triggers; it also creates/repopulates `context_items_fts` and adds its triggers. Evidence: `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:7`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:9`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:17`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:20`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:24`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:34`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:43`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:50`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:53`.\n\nThe migration runner discovers `*.sql`, requires `NNN_name.sql`, sorts by filename, computes SHA-256, strips comments, splits optional `-- DOWN`, and applies pending migrations in transactions before inserting `_schema_version`. Evidence: `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:44`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:47`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:53`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:72`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:202`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:239`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:242`. `001_baseline.sql` is a no-DDL sentinel that records the baseline created by `schema.sql`. Evidence: `migrations/001_baseline.sql:1`, `migrations/001_baseline.sql:4`, `migrations/001_baseline.sql:7`.\n\nConnection setup is WAL-first with FK enforcement and busy timeout; `shared-db.ts` executes `schema.sql`, then runs pending migrations, then backfills vec indexes if sqlite-vec exists. Evidence: `packages/openltm-core/src/shared-db.ts:31`, `packages/openltm-core/src/shared-db.ts:36`, `packages/openltm-core/src/shared-db.ts:37`, `packages/openltm-core/src/shared-db.ts:39`, `packages/openltm-core/src/shared-db.ts:42`, `packages/openltm-core/src/shared-db.ts:45`.\n\n## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n- **Claim** · Move from a single inline integer migration ladder toward checked-in numbered migration files with checksums. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:44`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:72`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/vector-index-schema.ts:1557` · **Maps-to** · `mcp_server/lib/search/vector-index-schema.ts` · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.90 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our v30 inline transaction/compatibility checks are strong, but per-file history and checksum auditability would make schema drift easier to diagnose.\n- **Claim** · Use a baseline sentinel when converting legacy inline migrations into file-backed history. · **Evidence** · `migrations/001_baseline.sql:1`, `migrations/001_baseline.sql:8` · **Maps-to** · new sub-packet · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · This fits our existing `schema_version` history without replaying old FSRS/causal/lineage migrations.\n- **Claim** · Treat FTS rebuilds as explicit migrations that repopulate from the source table and recreate triggers. · **Evidence** · `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:7`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:17`, `migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:24`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/vector-index-schema.ts:856` · **Maps-to** · `memory_fts` migration discipline · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.82 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · We already have trigger-kept FTS, but OpenLTM’s numbered FTS rebuild pattern is cleaner than burying rebuilds inside inline TypeScript migrations.\n- **Claim** · Do not copy OpenLTM’s embedding split as-is because our vectors are already separate profile-sharded SQLite files. · **Evidence** · `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:5`, `migrations/010_memory_embeddings_split.sql:25`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/constitutional/memory-db-file-topology.md:22`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/constitutional/memory-db-file-topology.md:31` · **Maps-to** · vector store topology · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.95 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our separate canonical DB plus active vector shard supersedes OpenLTM’s same-file side table.\n- **Claim** · Add pair-aware migration backups/checkpoints, not OpenLTM’s single-file backup. · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:76`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:231`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/constitutional/memory-db-file-topology.md:46` · **Maps-to** · checkpoint/migration safety · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.78 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Pre-migration backups transfer, but system-spec-kit must snapshot index and active vector shard together.\n- **Claim** · Publish an authoritative DB spec only if it is kept mechanically aligned with the runner. · **Evidence** · `docs/internal/DB-SPEC.md:496`, `docs/internal/DB-SPEC.md:521`, `packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:25` · **Maps-to** · new sub-packet · **Verdict** · DEFER · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.84 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · OpenLTM’s DB-SPEC is useful, but its `schema_migrations` vs `_schema_version` drift shows docs alone are not enough.\n\n## Negative knowledge\nDo not copy the split `schema_migrations`/`_schema_version` naming; it creates source-of-truth ambiguity.\n\nDo not trust same-file rollback unless `DOWN` SQL is executable; `parseMigration()` strips comments, while migrations like `002` have commented-only downs.\n\nDo not copy single-file DB assumptions; system-spec-kit’s index and vector shard must be backed up, checked, and restored as one unit.\n\nDo not replace FSRS/causal-edge schema with OpenLTM’s simpler decay/relation model; our current cognitive and causal surfaces are richer.\n\n## Open questions\nShould system-spec-kit’s inline v30 migration ladder be frozen behind a `001_baseline` and future changes moved to SQL files?\n\nShould `memory_health` add an explicit FTS5 `integrity-check`/rebuild report for `memory_fts`?\n\nShould migration checksums be stored per migration while preserving our existing single `schema_version` compatibility gate?\n\nDELTA_JSON: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"run\":1,\"iteration\":\"009\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"status\":\"insight\",\"focus\":\"Schema/DB design + migration discipline\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.55,\"findingsCount\":6,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: Move from a single inline integer migration ladder toward checked-in numbered migration files with checksums.\",\"ADOPT: Use a baseline sentinel when converting legacy inline migrations into file-backed history.\",\"ADAPT: Treat FTS rebuilds as explicit migrations that repopulate from the source table and recreate triggers.\"],\"sources\":[\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:5\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:7\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:11\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:25\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:27\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:32\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:127\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:129\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:132\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:137\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:142\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:147\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:155\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:157\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:164\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:169\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:174\",\"migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:7\",\"migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:9\",\"migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:17\",\"migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:20\",\"migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:24\",\"migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:34\",\"migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:43\",\"migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:50\",\"migrations/020_fts_coverage.sql:53\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:44\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:47\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:53\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:72\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:202\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:239\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/migrations.ts:242\",\"migrations/001_baseline.sql:1\",\"migrations/001_baseline.sql:4\",\"migrations/00... (line truncated to 2000 chars)","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":42,"totalLines":42,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-009.md","time":{"start":1780926450506,"end":1780926450551}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_036408d1c76c14fc016a26c7f25a5081918fdb9c6d42d8b2c5"}},"id":"prt_ea77d0b47001mSfXWGvHxuLIFo","sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","messageID":"msg_ea77cc18a001W0nhx4yXBV8BDy"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780926450570,"sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_FOMWV49Sim1GG2ZrFX7CtJzI","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-010.md","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-010.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 010 — learn() idempotency + cross-plugin write contract\n2: \n3: **Status:** complete · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.60 · **tokens:** 94338 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n4: \n5: ---\n6: \n7: ## Mechanism\n8: OpenLTM’s `learn()` idempotency is normalized-text keyed, not a verified hash: `normalizeKey()` lowercases, strips punctuation, collapses whitespace, trims, and truncates to 200 chars, while `memories.dedup_key` is `UNIQUE` (`packages/openltm-core/src/dedup.ts:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dedup.ts:6`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:45`). `learn()` scrubs secrets before dedupe, computes that key, then looks up duplicates by `WHERE dedup_key=?` only, with no category/project/workspace predicate (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:307`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:314`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:317`).\n9: \n10: On duplicate, OpenLTM reinforces the existing row: `confirm_count=confirm_count+1`, `last_confirmed_at=datetime('now')`, and `confidence=MIN(1.0, confidence+0.05)`, then returns `{ action: \"reinforced\", id, confirm_count }` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:321`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:324`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:347`). On first insert, it stores content/title/category/defaults, writes `dedup_key`, and returns `{ action: \"created\", id, confirm_count: 1 }` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:350`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:352`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:414`). Reinforcement affects lifecycle because decay never deprecates memories with `confirm_count>=5` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:246`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:258`).\n11: \n12: There are two queue concepts. Embedding generation uses a durable Honker queue named `ltm-embeddings` with `EMBED_MAX_ATTEMPTS = 5`; `learn()` enqueues an embedding job and falls back to inline embedding if enqueue returns `null` (`packages/openltm-core/src/queue/index.ts:12`, `packages/openltm-core/src/queue/index.ts:16`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:396`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:401`). The worker retries failures with exponential backoff from 5 seconds and acks on success (`packages/openltm-core/src/queue/worker.ts:25`, `packages/openltm-core/src/queue/worker.ts:55`, `packages/openltm-core/src/queue/worker.ts:60`). Separate write serialization is `WriteQueue`: a promise-tail queue wrapping DB writes in `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` / `COMMIT`, rolling back on error (`packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts:7`, `packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts:13`, `packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts:16`, `packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts:19`). Tests assert transaction wrapping, rollback, no interleaving, and recovery after rollback (`src/__tests__/writeQueue.test.ts:24`, `src/__tests__/writeQueue.test.ts:31`, `src/__tests__/writeQueue.test.ts:40`, `src/__tests__/writeQueue.test.ts:53`).\n13: \n14: Cross-runtime write access is adapter-specific today. OpenCode exposes `ltm_learn` and passes actor `opencode:ltm_learn` into core `learn()` (`packages/adapter-opencode/src/tools.ts:30`, `packages/adapter-opencode/src/tools.ts:44`, `packages/adapter-opencode/src/tools.ts:50`). Pi has a direct legacy `ltm_learn` path with actor `pi:ltm_learn`, while its newer bridge discovers MCP tools through `tools/list` and proxies `tools/call` (`packages/adapter-pi/src/tools.ts:42`, `packages/adapter-pi/src/tools.ts:61`, `packages/adapter-pi/src/tools.ts:67`, `packages/adapter-pi/src/index.ts:207`, `packages/adapter-pi/src/index.ts:211`, `packages/adapter-pi/src/index.ts:220`). The stable cross-plugin contract is roadmap, not fully current: Phase 5 says “Other plugins read/write memories through a versioned interface,” with “versioned MCP API + capability discovery” and exit criteria that another plugin can `recall+learn` without coupling (`docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:145`, `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:147`, `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:151`, `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:157`). PRD frames the same goal as a stable API so other plugins can write with category/source tags (`docs/internal/PRD.md:391`, `docs/internal/PRD.md:392`, `docs/internal/PRD.md:393`).\n15: \n16: ## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n17: - **Claim** · Add a tiny idempotent “learn/reinforce” write primitive beside `memory_save`, returning `created|reinforced|unchanged` and a reinforcement count · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:321`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:347` · **Maps-to** · new sub-packet · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our FSRS/validation signals are richer, but our broad spec-doc save path lacks this simple repeat-write contract for distilled facts.\n18: - **Claim** · Tie duplicate reinforcement to retention strength, but use FSRS/state transitions instead of OpenLTM’s raw `confirm_count>=5` shield · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:248`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:258` · **Maps-to** · FSRS decay + memory_validate · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.82 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · The intent transfers; our FSRS/co-activation should supersede the fixed threshold.\n19: - **Claim** · Publish a narrow stable write contract with capability discovery rather than asking other tools to understand the full 37-tool surface and spec-folder routing · **Evidence** · `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:147`, `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:151`, `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:157` · **Maps-to** · new sub-packet · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.88 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user/local does not remove cross-tool coupling; it makes a small contract easier to govern.\n20: - **Claim** · Make cross-runtime writes actor/provenance-aware by contract, not by adapter convention · **Evidence** · `packages/adapter-opencode/src/tools.ts:50`, `packages/adapter-pi/src/tools.ts:67`, `docs/internal/PRD.md:392` · **Maps-to** · memory_save provenance fields · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.80 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · We already have governed provenance knobs; the delta is requiring them in the stable write API.\n21: - **Claim** · Do not copy OpenLTM’s select-then-insert idempotency literally; use atomic upsert or serialized single-writer semantics · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:317`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:352`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:45` · **Maps-to** · memory_save / new learn API · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · HIGH · **Confidence** · 0.84 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our self-maintaining index should fail closed under concurrent MCP callers, not depend on an unscoped pre-read.\n22: \n23: ## Negative knowledge\n24: - Do not copy the 200-char normalized-text dedupe key as-is; it is not a hash and can over-merge across project/category boundaries.\n25: - Do not copy adapter-specific duplicated tool definitions; OpenLTM itself shows drift between OpenCode’s 5 tools and Pi’s 3 direct tools.\n26: - Do not replace system-spec-kit’s FSRS/causal-edge model with `confirm_count` thresholds; use reinforcement only as an input signal.\n27: - Do not expose the full maintenance/admin MCP surface as the cross-plugin write contract; plugins need a small, versioned write/read subset.\n28: \n29: ## Open questions\n30: - Should system-spec-kit’s idempotency key include `specFolder`, `contextType`, normalized content hash, and provenance actor, or should reinforcement intentionally cross folders?\n31: - Should reinforcement update FSRS scheduling directly, or only create a validation event consumed by existing reducers?\n32: - Should the stable write contract be MCP-only, or also a local CLI/JSON schema for non-MCP hooks?\n33: \n34: DELTA_JSON: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"run\":1,\"iteration\":\"010\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"learn() idempotency + cross-plugin write contract\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.6,\"findingsCount\":5,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: Add a tiny idempotent “learn/reinforce” write primitive beside `memory_save`, returning `created|reinforced|unchanged` and a reinforcement count\",\"ADAPT: Tie duplicate reinforcement to retention strength, but use FSRS/state transitions instead of OpenLTM’s raw `confirm_count>=5` shield\",\"ADOPT: Publish a narrow stable write contract with capability discovery rather than asking other tools to understand the full 37-tool surface and spec-folder ro\"],\"sources\":[\"packages/openltm-core/src/dedup.ts:5\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dedup.ts:6\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:45\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:307\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:314\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:317\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:321\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:324\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:347\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:350\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:352\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:414\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:246\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:258\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/queue/index.ts:12\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/queue/index.ts:16\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:396\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:401\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/queue/worker.ts:25\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/queue/worker.ts:55\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/queue/worker.ts:60\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts:7\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts:13\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts:16\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts:19\",\"src/__tests__/writeQueue.test.ts:24\",\"src/__tests__/writeQueue.test.ts:31\",\"src/__tests__/writeQueue.test.ts:40\",\"src/__tests__/writeQueue.test.ts:53\",\"packages/adapter-opencode/src/tools.ts:30\",\"packages/adapter-opencode/src/tools.ts:44\",\"packages/adapter-opencode/src/tools.ts... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(End of file - total 34 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 010 — learn() idempotency + cross-plugin write contract\n\n**Status:** complete · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.60 · **tokens:** 94338 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nOpenLTM’s `learn()` idempotency is normalized-text keyed, not a verified hash: `normalizeKey()` lowercases, strips punctuation, collapses whitespace, trims, and truncates to 200 chars, while `memories.dedup_key` is `UNIQUE` (`packages/openltm-core/src/dedup.ts:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dedup.ts:6`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:45`). `learn()` scrubs secrets before dedupe, computes that key, then looks up duplicates by `WHERE dedup_key=?` only, with no category/project/workspace predicate (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:307`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:314`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:317`).\n\nOn duplicate, OpenLTM reinforces the existing row: `confirm_count=confirm_count+1`, `last_confirmed_at=datetime('now')`, and `confidence=MIN(1.0, confidence+0.05)`, then returns `{ action: \"reinforced\", id, confirm_count }` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:321`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:324`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:347`). On first insert, it stores content/title/category/defaults, writes `dedup_key`, and returns `{ action: \"created\", id, confirm_count: 1 }` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:350`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:352`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:414`). Reinforcement affects lifecycle because decay never deprecates memories with `confirm_count>=5` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:246`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:258`).\n\nThere are two queue concepts. Embedding generation uses a durable Honker queue named `ltm-embeddings` with `EMBED_MAX_ATTEMPTS = 5`; `learn()` enqueues an embedding job and falls back to inline embedding if enqueue returns `null` (`packages/openltm-core/src/queue/index.ts:12`, `packages/openltm-core/src/queue/index.ts:16`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:396`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:401`). The worker retries failures with exponential backoff from 5 seconds and acks on success (`packages/openltm-core/src/queue/worker.ts:25`, `packages/openltm-core/src/queue/worker.ts:55`, `packages/openltm-core/src/queue/worker.ts:60`). Separate write serialization is `WriteQueue`: a promise-tail queue wrapping DB writes in `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` / `COMMIT`, rolling back on error (`packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts:7`, `packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts:13`, `packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts:16`, `packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts:19`). Tests assert transaction wrapping, rollback, no interleaving, and recovery after rollback (`src/__tests__/writeQueue.test.ts:24`, `src/__tests__/writeQueue.test.ts:31`, `src/__tests__/writeQueue.test.ts:40`, `src/__tests__/writeQueue.test.ts:53`).\n\nCross-runtime write access is adapter-specific today. OpenCode exposes `ltm_learn` and passes actor `opencode:ltm_learn` into core `learn()` (`packages/adapter-opencode/src/tools.ts:30`, `packages/adapter-opencode/src/tools.ts:44`, `packages/adapter-opencode/src/tools.ts:50`). Pi has a direct legacy `ltm_learn` path with actor `pi:ltm_learn`, while its newer bridge discovers MCP tools through `tools/list` and proxies `tools/call` (`packages/adapter-pi/src/tools.ts:42`, `packages/adapter-pi/src/tools.ts:61`, `packages/adapter-pi/src/tools.ts:67`, `packages/adapter-pi/src/index.ts:207`, `packages/adapter-pi/src/index.ts:211`, `packages/adapter-pi/src/index.ts:220`). The stable cross-plugin contract is roadmap, not fully current: Phase 5 says “Other plugins read/write memories through a versioned interface,” with “versioned MCP API + capability discovery” and exit criteria that another plugin can `recall+learn` without coupling (`docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:145`, `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:147`, `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:151`, `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:157`). PRD frames the same goal as a stable API so other plugins can write with category/source tags (`docs/internal/PRD.md:391`, `docs/internal/PRD.md:392`, `docs/internal/PRD.md:393`).\n\n## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n- **Claim** · Add a tiny idempotent “learn/reinforce” write primitive beside `memory_save`, returning `created|reinforced|unchanged` and a reinforcement count · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:321`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:347` · **Maps-to** · new sub-packet · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our FSRS/validation signals are richer, but our broad spec-doc save path lacks this simple repeat-write contract for distilled facts.\n- **Claim** · Tie duplicate reinforcement to retention strength, but use FSRS/state transitions instead of OpenLTM’s raw `confirm_count>=5` shield · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:248`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:258` · **Maps-to** · FSRS decay + memory_validate · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.82 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · The intent transfers; our FSRS/co-activation should supersede the fixed threshold.\n- **Claim** · Publish a narrow stable write contract with capability discovery rather than asking other tools to understand the full 37-tool surface and spec-folder routing · **Evidence** · `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:147`, `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:151`, `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:157` · **Maps-to** · new sub-packet · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.88 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user/local does not remove cross-tool coupling; it makes a small contract easier to govern.\n- **Claim** · Make cross-runtime writes actor/provenance-aware by contract, not by adapter convention · **Evidence** · `packages/adapter-opencode/src/tools.ts:50`, `packages/adapter-pi/src/tools.ts:67`, `docs/internal/PRD.md:392` · **Maps-to** · memory_save provenance fields · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.80 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · We already have governed provenance knobs; the delta is requiring them in the stable write API.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-010.md","text":"# Iteration 010 — learn() idempotency + cross-plugin write contract\n\n**Status:** complete · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.60 · **tokens:** 94338 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(xhigh) read-only\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nOpenLTM’s `learn()` idempotency is normalized-text keyed, not a verified hash: `normalizeKey()` lowercases, strips punctuation, collapses whitespace, trims, and truncates to 200 chars, while `memories.dedup_key` is `UNIQUE` (`packages/openltm-core/src/dedup.ts:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dedup.ts:6`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:45`). `learn()` scrubs secrets before dedupe, computes that key, then looks up duplicates by `WHERE dedup_key=?` only, with no category/project/workspace predicate (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:307`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:314`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:317`).\n\nOn duplicate, OpenLTM reinforces the existing row: `confirm_count=confirm_count+1`, `last_confirmed_at=datetime('now')`, and `confidence=MIN(1.0, confidence+0.05)`, then returns `{ action: \"reinforced\", id, confirm_count }` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:321`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:324`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:347`). On first insert, it stores content/title/category/defaults, writes `dedup_key`, and returns `{ action: \"created\", id, confirm_count: 1 }` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:350`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:352`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:414`). Reinforcement affects lifecycle because decay never deprecates memories with `confirm_count>=5` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:246`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:258`).\n\nThere are two queue concepts. Embedding generation uses a durable Honker queue named `ltm-embeddings` with `EMBED_MAX_ATTEMPTS = 5`; `learn()` enqueues an embedding job and falls back to inline embedding if enqueue returns `null` (`packages/openltm-core/src/queue/index.ts:12`, `packages/openltm-core/src/queue/index.ts:16`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:396`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:401`). The worker retries failures with exponential backoff from 5 seconds and acks on success (`packages/openltm-core/src/queue/worker.ts:25`, `packages/openltm-core/src/queue/worker.ts:55`, `packages/openltm-core/src/queue/worker.ts:60`). Separate write serialization is `WriteQueue`: a promise-tail queue wrapping DB writes in `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` / `COMMIT`, rolling back on error (`packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts:7`, `packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts:13`, `packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts:16`, `packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts:19`). Tests assert transaction wrapping, rollback, no interleaving, and recovery after rollback (`src/__tests__/writeQueue.test.ts:24`, `src/__tests__/writeQueue.test.ts:31`, `src/__tests__/writeQueue.test.ts:40`, `src/__tests__/writeQueue.test.ts:53`).\n\nCross-runtime write access is adapter-specific today. OpenCode exposes `ltm_learn` and passes actor `opencode:ltm_learn` into core `learn()` (`packages/adapter-opencode/src/tools.ts:30`, `packages/adapter-opencode/src/tools.ts:44`, `packages/adapter-opencode/src/tools.ts:50`). Pi has a direct legacy `ltm_learn` path with actor `pi:ltm_learn`, while its newer bridge discovers MCP tools through `tools/list` and proxies `tools/call` (`packages/adapter-pi/src/tools.ts:42`, `packages/adapter-pi/src/tools.ts:61`, `packages/adapter-pi/src/tools.ts:67`, `packages/adapter-pi/src/index.ts:207`, `packages/adapter-pi/src/index.ts:211`, `packages/adapter-pi/src/index.ts:220`). The stable cross-plugin contract is roadmap, not fully current: Phase 5 says “Other plugins read/write memories through a versioned interface,” with “versioned MCP API + capability discovery” and exit criteria that another plugin can `recall+learn` without coupling (`docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:145`, `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:147`, `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:151`, `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:157`). PRD frames the same goal as a stable API so other plugins can write with category/source tags (`docs/internal/PRD.md:391`, `docs/internal/PRD.md:392`, `docs/internal/PRD.md:393`).\n\n## Teachings for system-spec-kit\n- **Claim** · Add a tiny idempotent “learn/reinforce” write primitive beside `memory_save`, returning `created|reinforced|unchanged` and a reinforcement count · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:321`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:347` · **Maps-to** · new sub-packet · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.86 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our FSRS/validation signals are richer, but our broad spec-doc save path lacks this simple repeat-write contract for distilled facts.\n- **Claim** · Tie duplicate reinforcement to retention strength, but use FSRS/state transitions instead of OpenLTM’s raw `confirm_count>=5` shield · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:248`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:258` · **Maps-to** · FSRS decay + memory_validate · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.82 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · The intent transfers; our FSRS/co-activation should supersede the fixed threshold.\n- **Claim** · Publish a narrow stable write contract with capability discovery rather than asking other tools to understand the full 37-tool surface and spec-folder routing · **Evidence** · `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:147`, `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:151`, `docs/internal/ROADMAP.md:157` · **Maps-to** · new sub-packet · **Verdict** · ADOPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.88 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user/local does not remove cross-tool coupling; it makes a small contract easier to govern.\n- **Claim** · Make cross-runtime writes actor/provenance-aware by contract, not by adapter convention · **Evidence** · `packages/adapter-opencode/src/tools.ts:50`, `packages/adapter-pi/src/tools.ts:67`, `docs/internal/PRD.md:392` · **Maps-to** · memory_save provenance fields · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.80 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · We already have governed provenance knobs; the delta is requiring them in the stable write API.\n- **Claim** · Do not copy OpenLTM’s select-then-insert idempotency literally; use atomic upsert or serialized single-writer semantics · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:317`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:352`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:45` · **Maps-to** · memory_save / new learn API · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · HIGH · **Confidence** · 0.84 · **Why it transfers (or not)** · Our self-maintaining index should fail closed under concurrent MCP callers, not depend on an unscoped pre-read.\n\n## Negative knowledge\n- Do not copy the 200-char normalized-text dedupe key as-is; it is not a hash and can over-merge across project/category boundaries.\n- Do not copy adapter-specific duplicated tool definitions; OpenLTM itself shows drift between OpenCode’s 5 tools and Pi’s 3 direct tools.\n- Do not replace system-spec-kit’s FSRS/causal-edge model with `confirm_count` thresholds; use reinforcement only as an input signal.\n- Do not expose the full maintenance/admin MCP surface as the cross-plugin write contract; plugins need a small, versioned write/read subset.\n\n## Open questions\n- Should system-spec-kit’s idempotency key include `specFolder`, `contextType`, normalized content hash, and provenance actor, or should reinforcement intentionally cross folders?\n- Should reinforcement update FSRS scheduling directly, or only create a validation event consumed by existing reducers?\n- Should the stable write contract be MCP-only, or also a local CLI/JSON schema for non-MCP hooks?\n\nDELTA_JSON: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"run\":1,\"iteration\":\"010\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"learn() idempotency + cross-plugin write contract\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.6,\"findingsCount\":5,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: Add a tiny idempotent “learn/reinforce” write primitive beside `memory_save`, returning `created|reinforced|unchanged` and a reinforcement count\",\"ADAPT: Tie duplicate reinforcement to retention strength, but use FSRS/state transitions instead of OpenLTM’s raw `confirm_count>=5` shield\",\"ADOPT: Publish a narrow stable write contract with capability discovery rather than asking other tools to understand the full 37-tool surface and spec-folder ro\"],\"sources\":[\"packages/openltm-core/src/dedup.ts:5\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/dedup.ts:6\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:45\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:307\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:314\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:317\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:321\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:324\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:347\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:350\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:352\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:414\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:246\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:258\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/queue/index.ts:12\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/queue/index.ts:16\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:396\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:401\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/queue/worker.ts:25\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/queue/worker.ts:55\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/queue/worker.ts:60\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts:7\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts:13\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts:16\",\"packages/openltm-core/src/lib/writeQueue.ts:19\",\"src/__tests__/writeQueue.test.ts:24\",\"src/__tests__/writeQueue.test.ts:31\",\"src/__tests__/writeQueue.test.ts:40\",\"src/__tests__/writeQueue.test.ts:53\",\"packages/adapter-opencode/src/tools.ts:30\",\"packages/adapter-opencode/src/tools.ts:44\",\"packages/adapter-opencode/src/tools.ts... (line truncated to 2000 chars)","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":34,"totalLines":34,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/010-openltm-memory-architecture-teachings/iterations/iteration-010.md","time":{"start":1780926450548,"end":1780926450567}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_036408d1c76c14fc016a26c7f25a588191b0978b4848ddae1e"}},"id":"prt_ea77d0b4c001c4Oo1e2ACoDjCk","sessionID":"ses_1588409bdffe2CliO0RAdlpPIC","messageID":"msg_ea77cc18a001W0nhx4yXBV8BDy"}}
